{"title_page": "David O'Donoghue (historian)", "text_new": "'''David O'Donoghue''' (born 1952) is an Irish journalist and historian who has written two books on Irish-German relations during the Second World War. He has also worked as a journalist for [[RTE]] and for [[Agence France-Presse]] in Paris. He has a PhD from [[Dublin City University]].<ref>http://www.somervillepress.com/hitl.html</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''The Irish Army in the Congo 1960-1964: The Far Battalions''. Dublin, 2005.<ref>https://irishacademicpress.ie/product/the-irish-army-in-the-congo-1960-1964-the-far-battalions/</ref>\n* [https://www.jstor.org/stable/30002097 \"Army's Congo Mission Casts a Long Shadow\"], ''[[Irish Studies in International Affairs]]'', Vol. 17 (2006), pp.&nbsp;43\u201359. \n* ''The Devil\u2019s Deal: The IRA, Nazi Germany and the double life of Jim O\u2019Donovan''. Dublin, 2010.<ref>https://doi.org/10.1017/S0021121400003485</ref>\n* ''Hitler's Irish Voices: The story of German radio's wartime Irish service''. Dromore: Somerville Press, Dromore, 2014.<ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/hitler-s-irish-voices-by-david-o-donoghue-1.1918938</ref><ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=T-3Cb6zib2IC&pg=PA442</ref> {{ISBN|9780992736408}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*https://www.researchgate.net/publication/307803755_Nazis_on_the_State_Payroll_in_1930s_Ireland\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ODonoghue, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Irish journalists]]\n[[Category:Irish historians]]\n[[Category:Agence France-Presse journalists]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n\n\n{{Ireland-journalist-stub}}\n{{Ireland-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''David O'Donoghue''' (born 1952) is an Irish journalist and historian who has written two books on Irish-German relations during the Second World War. He has also worked as a journalist for [[RTE]] and for [[Agence France-Presse]] in Paris. He has a PhD from [[Dublin City University]].<ref>http://www.somervillepress.com/hitl.html</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''The Irish Army in the Congo 1960-1964: The Far Battalions''. Dublin, 2005.<ref>https://irishacademicpress.ie/product/the-irish-army-in-the-congo-1960-1964-the-far-battalions/</ref>\n* [https://www.jstor.org/stable/30002097 \"Army's Congo Mission Casts a Long Shadow\"], ''[[Irish Studies in International Affairs]]'', Vol. 17 (2006), pp. 43\u201359. \n* ''The Devil\u2019s Deal: The IRA, Nazi Germany and the double life of Jim O\u2019Donovan''. Dublin, 2010.<ref>https://doi.org/10.1017/S0021121400003485</ref>\n* ''Hitler's Irish Voices: The story of German radio's wartime Irish service''. Dromore: Somerville Press, Dromore, 2014.<ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/hitler-s-irish-voices-by-david-o-donoghue-1.1918938</ref><ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=T-3Cb6zib2IC&pg=PA442</ref> {{ISBN|9780992736408}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*https://www.researchgate.net/publication/307803755_Nazis_on_the_State_Payroll_in_1930s_Ireland\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ODonoghue, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Irish journalists]]\n[[Category:Irish historians]]\n[[Category:Agence France-Presse journalists]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n\n\n{{Ireland-journalist-stub}}\n{{Ireland-historian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_O%27Donoghue_(historian)"}
{"title_page": "David Northrup (historian)", "text_new": "'''David Northrup''' (born 1 May 1941) is [[emeritus professor]] of history at [[Boston College]]. He is the former president of the [[World History Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/17483.David_Northrup|title=David Northrup|website=www.goodreads.com}}</ref> and in 2017 received their Pioneers in World History Award.\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Seven Myths of Africa in World History''. Indianapolis : Hackett Publishing Company, Inc. 2017 {{ISBN|9781624666391}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apholt.com/2017/07/09/seven-myths-of-africa-in-world-history-an-interview-with-dr-david-northrup/|title=Seven Myths of Africa in World History: An Interview with Dr. David Northrup|last=Andrew Holt Ph. D|date=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Africa's Discovery of Europe: 1450-1850''. New York : Oxford UP, 2014. {{ISBN|9780199941216}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.history.ac.uk/history-online/book/isbn/0195140834|title=Africa's Discovery of Europe - History On-line|website=www.history.ac.uk}}</ref> \n* ''How English Became the Global Language''. New York : Palgrave Macmillan, 2013 {{ISBN|9781137303059}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.palgrave.com/gb/book/9781137303059|title=How English Became the Global Language - D. Northrup - Palgrave Macmillan|via=www.palgrave.com}}</ref>\n* ''Crosscurrents in the Black Atlantic, 1770-1965: A Brief History with Documents''. New York : Bedford/St. Martin's, 2010. {{ISBN|9780312442446}}\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/indenturedlabori00nort Indentured Labor in the Age of Imperialism, 1834-1922]'' New York : Cambridge University Press, 1995 {{ISBN|9780521485197}}\n* ''The Atlantic Slave Trade''. Lexington: Heath, 1994. (2002, 2001) {{ISBN|9780669331455}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review of The Atlantic Slave Trade|first=Kwasi|last=Sarfo|date=4 May 1996|journal=Africa Today|volume=43|issue=2|pages=209\u2013211|jstor = 4187099}}</ref> (Editor)\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/beyondbendinrive00nort Beyond the Bend in the River: African Labor in Eastern Zaire, 1865-1940]''. Athens, Ohio : Ohio University Center for International Studies, 1988. {{ISBN|9780896801516}}\n* ''Trade Without Rulers: Pre-Colonial Economic Development in South-Eastern Nigeria''. Oxford : Clarendon Press, 1978 {{ISBN|9780198227120}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review of TRADE WITHOUT RULERS: PRE-COLONIAL ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT IN SOUTHEASTERN NIGERIA|first=A. J. H.|last=LATHAM|date=4 May 1979|journal=History|volume=64|issue=211|pages=237\u2013238|jstor = 24411543}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*http://worldhistoryconnected.press.uillinois.edu/2.1/northrup.html\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Northrup, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Boston College faculty]]\n[[Category:American historians]]\n[[Category:Historians of slavery]]\n[[Category:Historians of Africa]]\n\n\n{{US-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''David Northrup''' (born 1 May 1941) is [[emeritus professor]] of history at [[Boston College]]. He is the former president of the [[World History Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/17483.David_Northrup|title=David Northrup|website=www.goodreads.com}}</ref> and in 2017 received their Pioneers in World History Award.\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Seven Myths of Africa in World History''. Indianapolis : Hackett Publishing Company, Inc. 2017 {{ISBN|9781624666391}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apholt.com/2017/07/09/seven-myths-of-africa-in-world-history-an-interview-with-dr-david-northrup/|title=Seven Myths of Africa in World History: An Interview with Dr. David Northrup|last=Andrew Holt Ph. D|date=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Africa's Discovery of Europe: 1450-1850''. New York : Oxford UP, 2014. {{ISBN|9780199941216}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.history.ac.uk/history-online/book/isbn/0195140834|title=Africa's Discovery of Europe 