{"title_page": "Bajaj CT 100", "text_new": "{{For|the color TV set|CT-100}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox Motorcycle|name=CT 100|image=[[File:Ct100 side.jpg|250px|Bajaj CT100]]|aka=|manufacturer=[[Bajaj Auto|Bajaj]]|parent_company=|production=2001-2006<br />2015-present|predecessor=[[Bajaj Boxer|Boxer]]|successor=[[Bajaj Platina|Platina]]|class=Commuter|engine=99.2&nbsp;cc and 115&nbsp;cc 4-stroke with Ride Control selector|top_speed=90 KM/H|power=8.1bhp|torque=8.05 Nm @ 4500 rpm|transmission=4-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]|suspension=Hydraulic, Telescopic Type (front)<br>Trailing arm with co-axial hydraulic shock absorb (rear)|brakes=Drum Brakes (Front and rear)|tires=Tube Type, Front 2.75/17, Rear 3.00/17|rake_trail=|wheelbase=1235 mm|length=1965 mm|width=770 mm|height=1072 mm|seat_height=678 mm|dry_weight=109 kg|wet_weight=|fuel_capacity=|related=|compression=|fuel_consumption=75 km/l|ignition=[[Capacitor discharge ignition]] (CDI)|turning_radius=}}\n'''Bajaj CT 100''' is a 100&nbsp;cc [[motorcycle]] built by [[Bajaj Auto]].\n\nThe CT 100 replaced the [[Bajaj Boxer]]. The new CT 100 sports the same four-stroke, 99.27&nbsp;cc engine as the Boxer. It also comes with a \"Ride Control\" switch which enables the rider to select between the economy and power mode. The CT 100 used to give up to 104&nbsp;km/l mileage. The previous variant was discontinued in 2006 from the Indian market and the CT 100 relaunched in the Indian market in 2015 with all new graphics and alloy wheels<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bajajauto.com/motor-bikes/ct-100/home|title=Bajaj CT 100, CT 100 BS6 Price, Mileage, Images, Colours|website=Bajaj Auto|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>. It spawned a variant of the much successful [[Bajaj Platina]] powered by a 115 cm<sup>3</sup> engine called the CT 110 in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bajajauto.com/motor-bikes/ct-110/home|title=Bajaj CT 110, CT 110 BS6 Price, Mileage, Images|website=Bajaj Auto|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>. It was the 9th best-selling motorcycle in [[India]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rushlane.com/best-selling-motorcycles-may-2019-12314457.html|title=Best selling motorcycles May 2019 - Hero Splendor at No 1|date=2019-06-24|website=RushLane|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.bajajauto.com/motor-bikes/ct-100/home Bajaj CT 100]\n{{Bajaj motorcycles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bajaj Ct 100}}\n[[Category:Bajaj motorcycles|CT 100]]\n\n\n{{Motorcycle-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the color TV set|CT-100}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox Motorcycle|name=CT 100|image=[[File:Ct100 side.jpg|250px|Bajaj CT100]]|aka=|manufacturer=[[Bajaj Auto|Bajaj]]|parent_company=|production=2001-2006<br />2015-present|predecessor=[[Bajaj Boxer|Boxer]]|successor=[[Bajaj Platina|Platina]]|class=Commuter|engine=99.2&nbsp;cc and 115&nbsp;cc 4-stroke with Ride Control selector|top_speed=90 KM/H|power=8.1bhp|torque=8.05 Nm @ 4500 rpm|transmission=4-speed [[manual]]|suspension=Hydraulic, Telescopic Type (front)<br>Trailing arm with co-axial hydraulic shock absorb (rear)|brakes=Drum Brakes (Front and rear)|tires=Tube Type, Front 2.75/17, Rear 3.00/17|rake_trail=|wheelbase=1235 mm|length=1965 mm|width=770 mm|height=1072 mm|seat_height=678 mm|dry_weight=109 kg|wet_weight=|fuel_capacity=|related=|compression=|fuel_consumption=75 km/l|ignition=[[Capacitor discharge ignition]] (CDI)|turning_radius=}}\n'''Bajaj CT 100''' is a 100&nbsp;cc [[motorcycle]] built by [[Bajaj Auto]].\n\nThe CT 100 replaced the [[Bajaj Boxer]]. The new CT 100 sports the same four-stroke, 99.27&nbsp;cc engine as the Boxer. It also comes with a \"Ride Control\" switch which enables the rider to select between the economy and power mode. The CT 100 used to give up to 104&nbsp;km/l mileage. The previous variant was discontinued in 2006 from the Indian market and the CT 100 relaunched in the Indian market in 2015 with all new graphics and alloy wheels<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bajajauto.com/motor-bikes/ct-100/home|title=Bajaj CT 100, CT 100 BS6 Price, Mileage, Images, Colours|website=Bajaj Auto|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>. It spawned a variant of the much successful [[Bajaj Platina]] powered by a 115 cm<sup>3</sup> engine called the CT 110 in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bajajauto.com/motor-bikes/ct-110/home|title=Bajaj CT 110, CT 110 BS6 Price, Mileage, Images|website=Bajaj Auto|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>. It was the 9th best-selling motorcycle in [[India]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rushlane.com/best-selling-motorcycles-may-2019-12314457.html|title=Best selling motorcycles May 2019 - Hero Splendor at No 1|date=2019-06-24|website=RushLane|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.bajajauto.com/motor-bikes/ct-100/home Bajaj CT 100]\n{{Bajaj motorcycles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bajaj Ct 100}}\n[[Category:Bajaj motorcycles|CT 100]]\n\n\n{{Motorcycle-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:manual\u2192manual transmission", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bajaj_CT_100"}
{"title_page": "Carlos Gardel", "text_new": "{{About|the person|the metro station|Carlos Gardel (Buenos Aires Underground)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name         = Carlos Gardel\n| image        = Gardel.jpg\n| caption      = Portrait of Gardel made by Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Silva in 1933.\n| background   = solo_singer\n| birth_name   = Charles Romuald Gard\u00e8s\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1890|12|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Toulouse]], [[France]]<ref name=UNESCO1986/>\n| Origin       = [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1935|6|24|1890|12|11|mf=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Colombia]]\n| genre        = [[Tango music|Tango]]\n| occupation   = [[Singer-Songwriter]]\n| years_active = 1917\u20131935\n| label =\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Carlos Gardel''' (born '''Charles Romuald Gard\u00e8s'''; 11 December 1890 \u2013 24 June 1935) was a [[French Argentine]] singer, songwriter, composer and actor, and the most prominent figure in the [[history of tango]].  Gardel's [[baritone]] voice and the dramatic phrasing of his lyrics made miniature masterpieces of his hundreds of three-minute tango recordings. Together with lyricist and long-time collaborator [[Alfredo Le Pera]], Gardel wrote several classic tangos.\n\nGardel died in an airplane crash at the height of his career, becoming an archetypal tragic hero mourned throughout Latin America. For many, Gardel embodies the soul of the tango style. He is commonly referred to as \"Carlitos\", \"El Zorzal\" (The [Song] Thrush), \"The King of Tango\", \"El Mago\" (The Wizard), \"El Morocho del Abasto\" (The Brunette boy from Abasto), and ironically \"El Mudo\" (The Mute).\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\n[[File:Gardel-Silva-1923.jpg|thumb|right|Gardel in [[gaucho]] clothes, 1923]]\nGardel was born to unmarried 25-year-old laundress Berthe Gard\u00e8s, the baby registered under the name Charles Romuald Gard\u00e8s in [[Tacuarembo]], [[Uruguay]], on 11 December 1890.<ref name=UNESCO1986/> The father of the baby boy was listed on his birth certificate as \"unknown\", but 11 days later Berthe Gard\u00e8s signed a statement establishing the baby's father as Paul Laserre, a married man who left Toulouse a few months before the baby was born.<ref name=Collier5/> Berthe Gard\u00e8s also left Toulouse, a little over a year later, likely to escape the social stigma of having a child born out of wedlock. In early 1893 in [[Bordeaux]], France, mother and son boarded the ship SS ''Don Pedro'' and sailed to Buenos Aires, arriving on 11 March 1893. Berthe Gard\u00e8s had her passport recorded upon arrival; she told immigration authorities that she was a widow. The two-year-old boy was recorded as Charles Gard\u00e8s.<ref name=Collier5/>\n\nGardel's mother settled at the western edge of the central [[San Nicol\u00e1s, Buenos Aires|San Nicol\u00e1s]] district of [[Buenos Aires]], at Calle Uruguay 162. She worked two blocks away on Calle Montevideo, pressing clothes in the French style, which commanded a relatively high price in the fashion-conscious city.<ref>Collier 1986, p. 6</ref> Gardel grew up speaking Spanish, not French, with friends and family calling him Carlos, the Spanish version of his French name, and often by the familiar diminutive form Carlitos.<ref>Collier 1986, pp. 7\u20138</ref>\n\nSome time after 1918, Laserre traveled from France to Buenos Aires to ask Berthe Gard\u00e8s, now called Do\u00f1a Berta, whether she would like to legitimize her son by marrying Laserre. This would have disrupted her story about being a widow. Gardel told his mother that if she did not need this man in her life, neither did he, closing the matter with \"I don't even wish to see him.\"<ref>Collier 1986, p. 7</ref>\n\n===Career===\nGardel began his singing career in bars and at private parties. He also sang with [[Francisco Martino]] and later in a trio with Martino and [[Jos\u00e9 Razzano]]. Gardel created the ''tango-canci\u00f3n'' in 1917 with his rendition of [[Pascual Contursi]] and [[Samuel Castriota]]'s ''[[Mi noche triste]]''. The recording sold 10,000 copies and was a hit throughout Latin America.<ref>Cunningham, Amy (3 July 2011). [http://www.soundsandcolours.com/articles/argentina/carlos-gardel-the-king-of-tango/ Carlos \"Gardel: The King of Tango\"], ''Sound and Colours''.</ref>\n\nGardel went on tour through Argentina, Uruguay, Chile, Brazil, [[Centro Espa\u00f1ol de Ponce|Puerto Rico]], Venezuela and Colombia, as well as making appearances in Paris, New York, Barcelona and Madrid. He sold 70,000 records in the first three months of a 1928 visit to Paris. As his popularity grew, he made a number of films for [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] in France and the U.S. While sentimental films such as ''[[Downward Slope|Cuesta abajo]]'' (1934) and ''[[El d\u00eda que me quieras (1935 film)|El d\u00eda que me quieras]]'' (1935) lack lasting dramatic value, they were outstanding showcases of his tremendous singing talents and movie star looks.\n\n===Romantic life===\nGardel was aware of the fact that much of his popularity was based on his attractiveness to women. In an effort to seem as if he were available to any woman, he sought to keep his love life secret. Gardel had one major girlfriend in his life: Isabel del Valle. He met del Valle in late 1920 when she was fourteen years of age.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://todayintango.wordpress.com/2011/03/16/1907-march-16-birth-of-isabel-del-valle/|title=1907, March 16 \u2013 BIRTH OF ISABEL DEL VALLE|date=2011-03-16|work=TODAY IN TANGO !|access-date=2018-03-13|language=en-US}}</ref> At the time, he was performing at the Esmeralda Theater in Buenos Aires. They were close for more than a decade. Gardel and del Valle were not seen together very often in public. Gardel's mother and del Valle's family helped make sure the relationship was not well known. Only Gardel's closest friends knew about it.<ref>Collier 1986, p. 73.</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVfIus_mXzAC&pg=PA31 |pages=15, 91, 119, 139 |title=La sonrisa de Gardel: Biograf\u00eda, mito y ficci\u00f3n |first=Jorge |last=Ruffinelli |publisher=Ediciones Trilce |year=2004 |isbn=9974323568 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nGardel arranged for del Valle to have a house; he provided money for her to live on. Around 1930 the relationship began to degrade. Gardel had his lawyer stop making payments to del Valle, who later married another man and moved to Uruguay. She was always respectful of the memory of Gardel, even when interviewed about him in late life for a 1980s television program.<ref>Collier 1986, pp. 121\u201322, 233, 210.</ref>\n\n===Death===\n[[File:Procesion Gardel 1936.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The coffin of Gardel moves down Florida Street in Buenos Aires]]\n[[File:La tumba de Carlos Gardel.jpg|thumb|Carlos Gardel's grave at La [[Chacarita Cemetery]]]]\n\nGardel died on 24 June 1935 in an airplane crash in [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia. Others who died included the pilot [[Ernesto Samper (pilot)|Ernesto Samper]], lyricist [[Alfredo Le Pera]], guitarists Guillermo Desiderio Barbieri and {{ill|\u00c1ngel Domingo Riverol|es}}, several business associates, and other friends of the group.<ref name=\"Clavell, M. 1996\">Clavell, M. (1996) (in Spanish), Biograf\u00eda. In: ''Los Mejores Tangos de Carlos Gardel''. Alfred Publ. Van Nuys, California.</ref> It is believed that a third guitarist, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aguilar Porr\u00e1s]], died a few days after the crash.<ref name=\"Clavell, M. 1996\"/>\n\nMillions of Gardel's fans throughout Latin America went into mourning. Hordes came to pay their respects as his body was taken from Colombia through New York City and [[Rio de Janeiro]]. Thousands rendered homage during the two days he lay in state in [[Montevideo]], the city in which his mother lived at the time. Gardel's body was laid to rest in [[La Chacarita Cemetery]] in Buenos Aires.\n\n==Birthplace controversy==\n[[File:MuseoCarlosGardel.jpg|thumb|right|Museo Carlos Gardel, a museum about the artist, located in [[Valle Ed\u00e9n]], [[Tacuaremb\u00f3]]]]\nThe place and year of Gardel's birth was a controversy that provoked debate; Toulouse, France, in 1890 was the most widely accepted version for many years.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVfIus_mXzAC&pg=PA31 |pages=31\u201332 |title=La sonrisa de Gardel: Biograf\u00eda, mito y ficci\u00f3n |first=Jorge |last=Ruffinelli |authorlink=Jorge Ruffinelli |publisher=Ediciones Trilce |year=2004 |isbn=9974323568 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=:es:Carlos Zubillaga |first=Carlos |last=Zubillaga |title=Carlos Gardel: tango inacabable |year=1976 |publisher=J\u00facar |pages=9, 103 |edition=2 |series=''Colecci\u00f3n Los Juglares'' |volume=33 |language=Spanish}}</ref> The Toulouse birthplace was confirmed in 2012 with the location of his birth certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1509532-fin-del-misterio-muestran-la-partida-de-nacimiento-de-gardel|title=Fin del misterio: muestran la partida de nacimiento de Gardel|trans-title=End of the mystery: they show Gardel's birth certificate |language=Spanish |author=Ver\u00f3nica Dema |date=September 20, 2012 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |accessdate=October 3, 2012}}</ref> Scholars such as [[Vanderbilt University]] history professor Simon Collier, [[University of Belgrano]] agriculture history professor Osvaldo Barsky and Uruguayan history professor [[Jorge Ruffinelli]] from [[Stanford University]] write about how Gardel was born in Toulouse, France, in 1890, and how he laid a false trail about his birthplace beginning in 1920, when he was almost 30.<ref name=Collier5>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/lifemusictimesof00coll |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/lifemusictimesof00coll/page/5 5] |title=The Life, Music, and Times of Carlos Gardel |first=Simon |last=Collier |publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press |year=1986 |isbn=0822984989}}</ref><ref name=Ruffinelli2004/><ref name=Barsky>{{cite book |first1=Juli\u00e1n |last1=Barsky |first2=Osvaldo |last2=Barsky |title=Gardel: La biograf\u00eda |publisher=Taurus |year=2004 |isbn=9870400132 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1920, Gardel first applied for Uruguayan citizenship; in Buenos Aires he went to the Uruguayan consulate to complete paperwork that said he was born in 1887 in Tacuaremb\u00f3, Uruguay. One month later he was issued a new Argentine identity card that listed him as a Uruguayan national. On 7 March 1923 he applied for citizenship in Argentina. On 1 May 1923 he took the oath of Argentine citizenship. Today, there is no absolute certainty regarding why he took these steps. The most likely reason for this act was to avoid problems with French authorities during an upcoming tour of France. As a French citizen by birth, Gardel had been required to register with the French military during the [[World War I|Great War]]. It is likely that Gardel never registered; his name is not found on any lists of registrants. Uruguay maintained a neutrality policy during the war, so Gardel probably chose Uruguayan citizenship on that basis.<ref name=Collier72>Collier 1986, p. 72.</ref>\n\nIn 1967, writer Erasmo Silva Cabrera started the modern dispute over Gardel's birthplace when he published arguments describing Gardel as having been born in Tacuaremb\u00f3, Uruguay.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004/><ref>{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel: el gran desconocido |first=Erasmo |last=Silva Cabrera |publisher=Ediciones Ciudadela |year=1967}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel |authorlink=:es:Blas Matamoro |first=Blas |last=Matamoro |publisher=Centro Editor de Am\u00e9rica Latina |year=1971 |pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Nelson Bayardo wrote a similar book in 1988.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004/><ref>{{cite book |title=Vida y milagros de Carlos Gardel |first=Nelson |last=Bayardo |publisher=Ediciones La Rep\u00fablica |year=1988}}</ref> In 1990, Eduardo Payss\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez published a book containing many biographical details supporting a birthplace of Tacuaremb\u00f3.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004/> The story is that Gardel was born in 1887 the son of influential Uruguayan landowner Carlos Escayola and Escayola's sister-in-law, 13-year-old Maria Lelia Oliva. The unwanted boy, named Carlos, was offered to Bertha Gardes who was passing through the area on a cabaret dance tour. Gardes took the boy with her back to France, where she was from. Later, she and the boy traveled again, this time to Buenos Aires, where they settled.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/7562848.stm |title=Argentina and Uruguay's tango row |date=16 August 2008 |work=From Our Own Correspondent |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> This version of events conflicts with scholarly accounts describing Gardes as an ordinary woman who [[Ironing|ironed]] and pressed clothing in Toulouse in 1890, not a touring dancer.<ref name=\"Sus Antecedentes Franceses\"/>\n\nIn the 1920s, Gardel's mother stopped working because his income was sufficient to support her modest lifestyle. She traveled regularly to France to visit her family in Toulouse. When Gardel was touring Europe for the first time, he and Razzano stopped for a few days in January 1924 in Toulouse where Gardel's mother introduced him to his uncle&nbsp;\u2013 her brother who had survived the war&nbsp;\u2013 and he met his blind grandmother who cried in happiness at the reunion.<ref>Collier 1986, p. 81.</ref> He revisited his family in Toulouse in 1934, after working in New York.\n\nAfter Gardel's death, his legal representative, Armando Defino, produced a handwritten will which he said was written by Gardel himself, stating he was born in Toulouse, France, to Berthe Gardes (1865\u20131943), and baptized with the name of Charles Romuald Gardes.<ref name=\"Sus Antecedentes Franceses\">{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel: Sus Antecedentes Franceses |first1=Monique Ruffi\u00e9 |last1=de Saint-Blancat |first2=Juan Carlos |last2=Esteban |first3=Georges |last3=Galopa |publisher=Corregidor |year=2006 |isbn=9500516349 |language=Spanish}}</ref> This statement agrees with the original birth certificate registered in Toulouse on 11 December 1890.<ref name=UNESCO1986>Bocaz, Luis (March 1986). [http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0006/000684/068421eo.pdf \"Tango Time\"], UNESCO ''Courier'', p. 11.</ref>\n\nIn his youth in Buenos Aires, Gardel's group of close friends called him \"''El francesito''\" (Frenchie), acknowledging his French origin.<ref>Collier 1986, pp. 14, 22.</ref> After 1920, Gardel gave contradictory and evasive stories about his birthplace, most likely because of the false papers he had filed.<ref name=Collier72/> Reporters often wrote that Gardel was Uruguayan, born in Tacuaremb\u00f3. In the newspaper ''El Tel\u00e9grafo'' (Paysand\u00fa, Uruguay, October 25, 1933), Gardel was reported as saying, \"I'm Uruguayan, born in Tacuaremb\u00f3\". In the June 1935 issue of ''Caretas'' magazine of Antioquia, Colombia, Gardel was reported as saying, \"My heart is Argentinian, but my soul is Uruguayan, because that is where I was born\". In 1931, Gardel wrote in a witnessed document, \"I am French, born in Toulouse, 11 December 1890, son of Berthe Gardes.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel : biograf\u00eda autorizada |first=Eliseo |last=Alvarez |publisher=De la Urraca |year=1995 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Compositions==\nGardel wrote the music and Alfredo Le Pera the lyrics for the following compositions:\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n*''Amargura'' (tango)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel - Cheating muchachita (Amargura)(1934.ogg]]\n*''Amores de Estudiante'' (waltz)\n*''Apure, Delantero Buey'' (song)\n*''Arrabal Amargo'' (tango)\n*''Caminito Soleado'' (song)\n*''Cheating Muchachita''\n*''Criollita, dec\u00ed que s\u00ed'' (song)\n*''Cuesta Abajo'' (tango)\n*''[[El d\u00eda que me quieras (song)|El d\u00eda que me quieras]]'' (song)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel-El dia que me quieras (1935).ogg]]\n*''Golondrinas'' (tango)\n*''Guitarra, Guitarra M\u00eda'' \n*''La Criolla''\n*''La Vida en un Trago''\n*''Lejana Tierra M\u00eda'' (song)\n*''Los Panchos en Buenos Aires''\n{{col-3}}\n*''Melod\u00eda de Arrabal'' (tango)\n*''[[Mi Buenos Aires querido (song)|Mi Buenos Aires Querido]]'' (tango, 1934)\n*''Olvido''\n*''Por tu Boca Roja''\n*''[[Por una cabeza]]'' (tango, 1935)\n**[[File:Por una cabeza carlos gardel.ogg]]\n*''Qui\u00e9reme''\n*''Recuerdo Malevo'' (tango)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel-Recuerdo malevo (1933).ogg]]\n*''Rubias de New York'' (foxtrot)\n*''Soledad'' (tango)\n**[[File:Soledad-Tango.ogg]]\n*''Suerte Negra'' (waltz)\n*''Sus ojos se Cerraron'' (tango)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel-Sus ojos se cerraron (1935).ogg]]\n*''Viejos Tiempos'' (tango)\n*''[[Volver (tango)|Volver]]'' (tango, 1934)\n**[[File:CarlosGardel-Volver(1935).ogg]]\n*''Volvi\u00f3 una Noche'' (tango)\n{{col-3}}\n[[File:Razzano Gardel 1926.jpg|thumb|[[Jos\u00e9 Razzano]] (left) and Gardel in Gardel's mother's house, 1926]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* ''Flor de Durazno'' (1917) (silent) <sup>1</sup>\n*''A\u00f1oranzas'' (1930, short)\n*''Canchero'' (1930)\n*''El Carretero'' (1930, short)\n*''El Quinielero'' (1930, short) \n*''Enfund\u00e1 la Mandolina'' (1930, short)\n*''\u00a1Leguisamo Solo!'' (1930, short)\n*''Mano a Mano'' (1930, short)\n*''Padrino Pelado'' (1930, short) \n*''Tengo Miedo'' (1930) \n*''Viejo Smoking'' (1930, short)\n{{col-3}}\n*''Yira, Yira'' (1930, short)\n* ''[[The Lights of Buenos Aires]]'' (1931) (filmed in Paris)\n* ''Esperame'' (1932)\n* ''[[The house is serious|La Casa es Seria]]'' (1932)\n* ''[[Suburban Melody]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[Downward Slope]]'' (1934)\n*''[[The Tango on Broadway]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[El d\u00eda que me quieras (1935 film)|El d\u00eda que me quieras]]'' (1935)\n* ''Cazadores de Estrellas'' (1935)\n* ''Tango Bar'' (1935)<ref name=\"Finkielman2003\">{{cite book|author=Jorge Finkielman|title=The Film Industry in Argentina: An Illustrated Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pbhjvdIt6FoC&pg=PA194|date=24 December 2003|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8344-0|page=194}}</ref>\n{{col-3}}\n[[File:Carlos Gardel Rubias de New York.JPG|thumb|right|Gardel in New York promoting 1934's ''El Tango en Broadway'']]\n{{col-end}}\n\nNotes:\n* <sup>1</sup> <small>''Gardel's first film, directed by Francisco Defilippis Novoa and made in collaboration with Celestino Petray.''</small><ref name=Barsky/>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{Refimprove section|date=May 2017}}\nGardel's legacy is intimately tied with the [[tango]]. For his tango singing, Gardel is still revered from Tokyo to Buenos Aires. A popular saying in Argentina, which serves as a testimony to his long-lived popularity, claims, \"Gardel sings better every day.\" Another commonly used phrase in Argentina (and some other Latin American countries) which asserts that ''Veinte a\u00f1os no es nada'' (''Twenty years is nothing''), comes from his song ''[[Volver (tango)|Volver]]'' (1934). Another common Argentine phrase is ''soy/sos Gardel y Le Pera'' (''I'm/You are Gardel and Le Pera'') referring to the greatness of both; used when somebody excels at something.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nIn the neighborhood of Abasto, Buenos Aires, the Carlos Gardel Museum opened in 2003, in a house that Gardel bought for his mother in 1927, and where he also lived from 1927 to 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turismo.buenosaires.gob.ar/en/otros-establecimientos/museo-casa-carlos-gardel|title=Museo Casa Carlos Gardel|website=Official English Website for the City of Buenos Aires|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> Another Carlos Gardel Museum opened in 1999 in Valle Ed\u00e9n, an old farm site {{convert|23|km|abbr=on}} south of Tacuaremb\u00f3, Uruguay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.uruguay.com/uruguay_detail_675_carlos_gardel_museum.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303171246/http://english.uruguay.com/uruguay_detail_675_carlos_gardel_museum.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 March 2016 |title=Carlos Gardel Museum |publisher=Uruguay.com |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Uruguay produced a Gardel stamp calling him the \"immortal Tacuaremboan\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Feuding Uruguay, Argentina unite to preserve tango |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/latino/feuding-uruguay-argentina-unite-preserve-tango-article-1.412560?pgno=1 |page=2 |date=11 May 2009 |work=New York Daily News |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> On March 16, 2011, the United States Postal Service issued a set of five \"Latin Music Legends\" stamps including one picturing Carlos Gardel.<ref>USPS Postal News Release No. 11-024 (March 16, 2011)</ref>\n\n===In literature===\n[[Ant\u00f3nio Lobo Antunes]] wrote a novel entitled ''The Death of Carlos Gardel'', in which one of the characters believes that Gardel did not die in the plane crash in 1935.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nGardel appears as a fictionalized character in the play ''El d\u00eda que me quieras'' (1979) by the Venezuelan writer [[Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Cabrujas]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n===In film===\nIn the 1939 biopic ''[[The Life of Carlos Gardel]]'', he is portrayed by [[Hugo del Carril]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n''[[Doble o Nada]]'' starring Dario Grandinetti and Aitana S\u00e1nchez-Gij\u00f3n was released by Maverick in April 2003. It is a fictional story about a struggling Argentine tango singer who looks and sings like Gardel, and a woman admirer of Gardel, who encounters Franchi.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tango singers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquotelang|es}}\n{{wikisource-author}}\n{{Commons category|Carlos Gardel}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p78844}}\n* {{IMDb name|0306624}}\n* {{Cinenacional name|id=carlos-gardel|old_id=1813}}\n* [http://www.todotango.com/english/gardel/ Carlos Gardel] at Todotango.com\n* [http://soundsandcolours.com/articles/argentina/carlos-gardel-the-king-of-tango-8318/ Carlos Gardel: King of Tango] at Sounds and Colours\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardel, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Argentine singers]]\n[[Category:Argentine male singers]]\n[[Category:Burials at La Chacarita Cemetery]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Male tango film actors]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures contract players]]\n[[Category:People with acquired Argentine citizenship]]\n[[Category:Tango singers]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in 1935]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the person|the metro station|Carlos Gardel (Buenos Aires Underground)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name         = Carlos Gardel\n| image        = Gardel.jpg\n| caption      = Portrait of Gardel made by Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Silva in 1933.\n| background   = solo_singer\n| birth_name   = Charles Romuald Gard\u00e8s\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1890|12|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Toulouse]], [[France]]<ref name=UNESCO1986/>\n| Origin       = [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1935|6|24|1890|12|11|mf=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Colombia]]\n| genre        = [[Tango music|Tango]]\n| occupation   = [[Singer-Songwriter]]\n| years_active = 1917\u20131935\n| label =\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''Carlos Gardel''' (born '''Charles Romuald Gard\u00e8s'''; 11 December 1890 \u2013 24 June 1935) was a [[French Argentine]] singer, songwriter, composer and actor, and the most prominent figure in the [[history of tango]].  Gardel's [[baritone]] voice and the dramatic phrasing of his lyrics made miniature masterpieces of his hundreds of three-minute tango recordings. Together with lyricist and long-time collaborator [[Alfredo Le Pera]], Gardel wrote several classic tangos.\n\nGardel died in an airplane crash at the height of his career, becoming an archetypal tragic hero mourned throughout Latin America. For many, Gardel embodies the soul of the tango style. He is commonly referred to as \"Carlitos\", \"El Zorzal\" (The [Song] Thrush), \"The King of Tango\", \"El Mago\" (The Wizard), \"El Morocho del Abasto\" (The Brunette boy from Abasto), and ironically \"El Mudo\" (The Mute).\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\n[[File:Gardel-Silva-1923.jpg|thumb|right|Gardel in [[gaucho]] clothes, 1923]]\nGardel was born to unmarried 25-year-old laundress Berthe Gard\u00e8s, the baby registered under the name Charles Romuald Gard\u00e8s in [[Toulouse]], [[France]], on 11 December 1890.<ref name=UNESCO1986/> The father of the baby boy was listed on his birth certificate as \"unknown\", but 11 days later Berthe Gard\u00e8s signed a statement establishing the baby's father as Paul Laserre, a married man who left Toulouse a few months before the baby was born.<ref name=Collier5/> Berthe Gard\u00e8s also left Toulouse, a little over a year later, likely to escape the social stigma of having a child born out of wedlock. In early 1893 in [[Bordeaux]], France, mother and son boarded the ship SS ''Don Pedro'' and sailed to Buenos Aires, arriving on 11 March 1893. Berthe Gard\u00e8s had her passport recorded upon arrival; she told immigration authorities that she was a widow. The two-year-old boy was recorded as Charles Gard\u00e8s.<ref name=Collier5/>\n\nGardel's mother settled at the western edge of the central [[San Nicol\u00e1s, Buenos Aires|San Nicol\u00e1s]] district of [[Buenos Aires]], at Calle Uruguay 162. She worked two blocks away on Calle Montevideo, pressing clothes in the French style, which commanded a relatively high price in the fashion-conscious city.<ref>Collier 1986, p. 6</ref> Gardel grew up speaking Spanish, not French, with friends and family calling him Carlos, the Spanish version of his French name, and often by the familiar diminutive form Carlitos.<ref>Collier 1986, pp. 7\u20138</ref>\n\nSome time after 1918, Laserre traveled from France to Buenos Aires to ask Berthe Gard\u00e8s, now called Do\u00f1a Berta, whether she would like to legitimize her son by marrying Laserre. This would have disrupted her story about being a widow. Gardel told his mother that if she did not need this man in her life, neither did he, closing the matter with \"I don't even wish to see him.\"<ref>Collier 1986, p. 7</ref>\n\n===Career===\nGardel began his singing career in bars and at private parties. He also sang with [[Francisco Martino]] and later in a trio with Martino and [[Jos\u00e9 Razzano]]. Gardel created the ''tango-canci\u00f3n'' in 1917 with his rendition of [[Pascual Contursi]] and [[Samuel Castriota]]'s ''[[Mi noche triste]]''. The recording sold 10,000 copies and was a hit throughout Latin America.<ref>Cunningham, Amy (3 July 2011). [http://www.soundsandcolours.com/articles/argentina/carlos-gardel-the-king-of-tango/ Carlos \"Gardel: The King of Tango\"], ''Sound and Colours''.</ref>\n\nGardel went on tour through Argentina, Uruguay, Chile, Brazil, [[Centro Espa\u00f1ol de Ponce|Puerto Rico]], Venezuela and Colombia, as well as making appearances in Paris, New York, Barcelona and Madrid. He sold 70,000 records in the first three months of a 1928 visit to Paris. As his popularity grew, he made a number of films for [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] in France and the U.S. While sentimental films such as ''[[Downward Slope|Cuesta abajo]]'' (1934) and ''[[El d\u00eda que me quieras (1935 film)|El d\u00eda que me quieras]]'' (1935) lack lasting dramatic value, they were outstanding showcases of his tremendous singing talents and movie star looks.\n\n===Romantic life===\nGardel was aware of the fact that much of his popularity was based on his attractiveness to women. In an effort to seem as if he were available to any woman, he sought to keep his love life secret. Gardel had one major girlfriend in his life: Isabel del Valle. He met del Valle in late 1920 when she was fourteen years of age.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://todayintango.wordpress.com/2011/03/16/1907-march-16-birth-of-isabel-del-valle/|title=1907, March 16 \u2013 BIRTH OF ISABEL DEL VALLE|date=2011-03-16|work=TODAY IN TANGO !|access-date=2018-03-13|language=en-US}}</ref> At the time, he was performing at the Esmeralda Theater in Buenos Aires. They were close for more than a decade. Gardel and del Valle were not seen together very often in public. Gardel's mother and del Valle's family helped make sure the relationship was not well known. Only Gardel's closest friends knew about it.<ref>Collier 1986, p. 73.</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVfIus_mXzAC&pg=PA31 |pages=15, 91, 119, 139 |title=La sonrisa de Gardel: Biograf\u00eda, mito y ficci\u00f3n |first=Jorge |last=Ruffinelli |publisher=Ediciones Trilce |year=2004 |isbn=9974323568 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nGardel arranged for del Valle to have a house; he provided money for her to live on. Around 1930 the relationship began to degrade. Gardel had his lawyer stop making payments to del Valle, who later married another man and moved to Uruguay. She was always respectful of the memory of Gardel, even when interviewed about him in late life for a 1980s television program.<ref>Collier 1986, pp. 121\u201322, 233, 210.</ref>\n\n===Death===\n[[File:Procesion Gardel 1936.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The coffin of Gardel moves down Florida Street in Buenos Aires]]\n[[File:La tumba de Carlos Gardel.jpg|thumb|Carlos Gardel's grave at La [[Chacarita Cemetery]]]]\n\nGardel died on 24 June 1935 in an airplane crash in [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia. Others who died included the pilot [[Ernesto Samper (pilot)|Ernesto Samper]], lyricist [[Alfredo Le Pera]], guitarists Guillermo Desiderio Barbieri and {{ill|\u00c1ngel Domingo Riverol|es}}, several business associates, and other friends of the group.<ref name=\"Clavell, M. 1996\">Clavell, M. (1996) (in Spanish), Biograf\u00eda. In: ''Los Mejores Tangos de Carlos Gardel''. Alfred Publ. Van Nuys, California.</ref> It is believed that a third guitarist, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aguilar Porr\u00e1s]], died a few days after the crash.<ref name=\"Clavell, M. 1996\"/>\n\nMillions of Gardel's fans throughout Latin America went into mourning. Hordes came to pay their respects as his body was taken from Colombia through New York City and [[Rio de Janeiro]]. Thousands rendered homage during the two days he lay in state in [[Montevideo]], the city in which his mother lived at the time. Gardel's body was laid to rest in [[La Chacarita Cemetery]] in Buenos Aires.\n\n==Birthplace controversy==\n[[File:MuseoCarlosGardel.jpg|thumb|right|Museo Carlos Gardel, a museum about the artist, located in [[Valle Ed\u00e9n]], [[Tacuaremb\u00f3]]]]\nThe place and year of Gardel's birth was a controversy that provoked debate; Toulouse, France, in 1890 was the most widely accepted version for many years.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVfIus_mXzAC&pg=PA31 |pages=31\u201332 |title=La sonrisa de Gardel: Biograf\u00eda, mito y ficci\u00f3n |first=Jorge |last=Ruffinelli |authorlink=Jorge Ruffinelli |publisher=Ediciones Trilce |year=2004 |isbn=9974323568 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=:es:Carlos Zubillaga |first=Carlos |last=Zubillaga |title=Carlos Gardel: tango inacabable |year=1976 |publisher=J\u00facar |pages=9, 103 |edition=2 |series=''Colecci\u00f3n Los Juglares'' |volume=33 |language=Spanish}}</ref> The Toulouse birthplace was confirmed in 2012 with the location of his birth certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1509532-fin-del-misterio-muestran-la-partida-de-nacimiento-de-gardel|title=Fin del misterio: muestran la partida de nacimiento de Gardel|trans-title=End of the mystery: they show Gardel's birth certificate |language=Spanish |author=Ver\u00f3nica Dema |date=September 20, 2012 |work=La Naci\u00f3n |accessdate=October 3, 2012}}</ref> Scholars such as [[Vanderbilt University]] history professor Simon Collier, [[University of Belgrano]] agriculture history professor Osvaldo Barsky and Uruguayan history professor [[Jorge Ruffinelli]] from [[Stanford University]] write about how Gardel was born in Toulouse, France, in 1890, and how he laid a false trail about his birthplace beginning in 1920, when he was almost 30.<ref name=Collier5>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/lifemusictimesof00coll |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/lifemusictimesof00coll/page/5 5] |title=The Life, Music, and Times of Carlos Gardel |first=Simon |last=Collier |publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press |year=1986 |isbn=0822984989}}</ref><ref name=Ruffinelli2004/><ref name=Barsky>{{cite book |first1=Juli\u00e1n |last1=Barsky |first2=Osvaldo |last2=Barsky |title=Gardel: La biograf\u00eda |publisher=Taurus |year=2004 |isbn=9870400132 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1920, Gardel first applied for Uruguayan citizenship; in Buenos Aires he went to the Uruguayan consulate to complete paperwork that said he was born in 1887 in Tacuaremb\u00f3, Uruguay. One month later he was issued a new Argentine identity card that listed him as a Uruguayan national. On 7 March 1923 he applied for citizenship in Argentina. On 1 May 1923 he took the oath of Argentine citizenship. Today, there is no absolute certainty regarding why he took these steps. The most likely reason for this act was to avoid problems with French authorities during an upcoming tour of France. As a French citizen by birth, Gardel had been required to register with the French military during the [[World War I|Great War]]. It is likely that Gardel never registered; his name is not found on any lists of registrants. Uruguay maintained a neutrality policy during the war, so Gardel probably chose Uruguayan citizenship on that basis.<ref name=Collier72>Collier 1986, p. 72.</ref>\n\nIn 1967, writer Erasmo Silva Cabrera started the modern dispute over Gardel's birthplace when he published arguments describing Gardel as having been born in Tacuaremb\u00f3, Uruguay.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004/><ref>{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel: el gran desconocido |first=Erasmo |last=Silva Cabrera |publisher=Ediciones Ciudadela |year=1967}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel |authorlink=:es:Blas Matamoro |first=Blas |last=Matamoro |publisher=Centro Editor de Am\u00e9rica Latina |year=1971 |pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Nelson Bayardo wrote a similar book in 1988.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004/><ref>{{cite book |title=Vida y milagros de Carlos Gardel |first=Nelson |last=Bayardo |publisher=Ediciones La Rep\u00fablica |year=1988}}</ref> In 1990, Eduardo Payss\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez published a book containing many biographical details supporting a birthplace of Tacuaremb\u00f3.<ref name=Ruffinelli2004/> The story is that Gardel was born in 1887 the son of influential Uruguayan landowner Carlos Escayola and Escayola's sister-in-law, 13-year-old Maria Lelia Oliva. The unwanted boy, named Carlos, was offered to Bertha Gardes who was passing through the area on a cabaret dance tour. Gardes took the boy with her back to France, where she was from. Later, she and the boy traveled again, this time to Buenos Aires, where they settled.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/7562848.stm |title=Argentina and Uruguay's tango row |date=16 August 2008 |work=From Our Own Correspondent |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> This version of events conflicts with scholarly accounts describing Gardes as an ordinary woman who [[Ironing|ironed]] and pressed clothing in Toulouse in 1890, not a touring dancer.<ref name=\"Sus Antecedentes Franceses\"/>\n\nIn the 1920s, Gardel's mother stopped working because his income was sufficient to support her modest lifestyle. She traveled regularly to France to visit her family in Toulouse. When Gardel was touring Europe for the first time, he and Razzano stopped for a few days in January 1924 in Toulouse where Gardel's mother introduced him to his uncle&nbsp;\u2013 her brother who had survived the war&nbsp;\u2013 and he met his blind grandmother who cried in happiness at the reunion.<ref>Collier 1986, p. 81.</ref> He revisited his family in Toulouse in 1934, after working in New York.\n\nAfter Gardel's death, his legal representative, Armando Defino, produced a handwritten will which he said was written by Gardel himself, stating he was born in Toulouse, France, to Berthe Gardes (1865\u20131943), and baptized with the name of Charles Romuald Gardes.<ref name=\"Sus Antecedentes Franceses\">{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel: Sus Antecedentes Franceses |first1=Monique Ruffi\u00e9 |last1=de Saint-Blancat |first2=Juan Carlos |last2=Esteban |first3=Georges |last3=Galopa |publisher=Corregidor |year=2006 |isbn=9500516349 |language=Spanish}}</ref> This statement agrees with the original birth certificate registered in Toulouse on 11 December 1890.<ref name=UNESCO1986>Bocaz, Luis (March 1986). [http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0006/000684/068421eo.pdf \"Tango Time\"], UNESCO ''Courier'', p. 11.</ref>\n\nIn his youth in Buenos Aires, Gardel's group of close friends called him \"''El francesito''\" (Frenchie), acknowledging his French origin.<ref>Collier 1986, pp. 14, 22.</ref> After 1920, Gardel gave contradictory and evasive stories about his birthplace, most likely because of the false papers he had filed.<ref name=Collier72/> Reporters often wrote that Gardel was Uruguayan, born in Tacuaremb\u00f3. In the newspaper ''El Tel\u00e9grafo'' (Paysand\u00fa, Uruguay, October 25, 1933), Gardel was reported as saying, \"I'm Uruguayan, born in Tacuaremb\u00f3\". In the June 1935 issue of ''Caretas'' magazine of Antioquia, Colombia, Gardel was reported as saying, \"My heart is Argentinian, but my soul is Uruguayan, because that is where I was born\". In 1931, Gardel wrote in a witnessed document, \"I am French, born in Toulouse, 11 December 1890, son of Berthe Gardes.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Carlos Gardel : biograf\u00eda autorizada |first=Eliseo |last=Alvarez |publisher=De la Urraca |year=1995 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Compositions==\nGardel wrote the music and Alfredo Le Pera the lyrics for the following compositions:\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n*''Amargura'' (tango)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel - Cheating muchachita (Amargura)(1934.ogg]]\n*''Amores de Estudiante'' (waltz)\n*''Apure, Delantero Buey'' (song)\n*''Arrabal Amargo'' (tango)\n*''Caminito Soleado'' (song)\n*''Cheating Muchachita''\n*''Criollita, dec\u00ed que s\u00ed'' (song)\n*''Cuesta Abajo'' (tango)\n*''[[El d\u00eda que me quieras (song)|El d\u00eda que me quieras]]'' (song)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel-El dia que me quieras (1935).ogg]]\n*''Golondrinas'' (tango)\n*''Guitarra, Guitarra M\u00eda'' \n*''La Criolla''\n*''La Vida en un Trago''\n*''Lejana Tierra M\u00eda'' (song)\n*''Los Panchos en Buenos Aires''\n{{col-3}}\n*''Melod\u00eda de Arrabal'' (tango)\n*''[[Mi Buenos Aires querido (song)|Mi Buenos Aires Querido]]'' (tango, 1934)\n*''Olvido''\n*''Por tu Boca Roja''\n*''[[Por una cabeza]]'' (tango, 1935)\n**[[File:Por una cabeza carlos gardel.ogg]]\n*''Qui\u00e9reme''\n*''Recuerdo Malevo'' (tango)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel-Recuerdo malevo (1933).ogg]]\n*''Rubias de New York'' (foxtrot)\n*''Soledad'' (tango)\n**[[File:Soledad-Tango.ogg]]\n*''Suerte Negra'' (waltz)\n*''Sus ojos se Cerraron'' (tango)\n**[[File:Carlos Gardel-Sus ojos se cerraron (1935).ogg]]\n*''Viejos Tiempos'' (tango)\n*''[[Volver (tango)|Volver]]'' (tango, 1934)\n**[[File:CarlosGardel-Volver(1935).ogg]]\n*''Volvi\u00f3 una Noche'' (tango)\n{{col-3}}\n[[File:Razzano Gardel 1926.jpg|thumb|[[Jos\u00e9 Razzano]] (left) and Gardel in Gardel's mother's house, 1926]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n* ''Flor de Durazno'' (1917) (silent) <sup>1</sup>\n*''A\u00f1oranzas'' (1930, short)\n*''Canchero'' (1930)\n*''El Carretero'' (1930, short)\n*''El Quinielero'' (1930, short) \n*''Enfund\u00e1 la Mandolina'' (1930, short)\n*''\u00a1Leguisamo Solo!'' (1930, short)\n*''Mano a Mano'' (1930, short)\n*''Padrino Pelado'' (1930, short) \n*''Tengo Miedo'' (1930) \n*''Viejo Smoking'' (1930, short)\n{{col-3}}\n*''Yira, Yira'' (1930, short)\n* ''[[The Lights of Buenos Aires]]'' (1931) (filmed in Paris)\n* ''Esperame'' (1932)\n* ''[[The house is serious|La Casa es Seria]]'' (1932)\n* ''[[Suburban Melody]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[Downward Slope]]'' (1934)\n*''[[The Tango on Broadway]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[El d\u00eda que me quieras (1935 film)|El d\u00eda que me quieras]]'' (1935)\n* ''Cazadores de Estrellas'' (1935)\n* ''Tango Bar'' (1935)<ref name=\"Finkielman2003\">{{cite book|author=Jorge Finkielman|title=The Film Industry in Argentina: An Illustrated Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pbhjvdIt6FoC&pg=PA194|date=24 December 2003|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8344-0|page=194}}</ref>\n{{col-3}}\n[[File:Carlos Gardel Rubias de New York.JPG|thumb|right|Gardel in New York promoting 1934's ''El Tango en Broadway'']]\n{{col-end}}\n\nNotes:\n* <sup>1</sup> <small>''Gardel's first film, directed by Francisco Defilippis Novoa and made in collaboration with Celestino Petray.''</small><ref name=Barsky/>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{Refimprove section|date=May 2017}}\nGardel's legacy is intimately tied with the [[tango]]. For his tango singing, Gardel is still revered from Tokyo to Buenos Aires. A popular saying in Argentina, which serves as a testimony to his long-lived popularity, claims, \"Gardel sings better every day.\" Another commonly used phrase in Argentina (and some other Latin American countries) which asserts that ''Veinte a\u00f1os no es nada'' (''Twenty years is nothing''), comes from his song ''[[Volver (tango)|Volver]]'' (1934). Another common Argentine phrase is ''soy/sos Gardel y Le Pera'' (''I'm/You are Gardel and Le Pera'') referring to the greatness of both; used when somebody excels at something.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nIn the neighborhood of Abasto, Buenos Aires, the Carlos Gardel Museum opened in 2003, in a house that Gardel bought for his mother in 1927, and where he also lived from 1927 to 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turismo.buenosaires.gob.ar/en/otros-establecimientos/museo-casa-carlos-gardel|title=Museo Casa Carlos Gardel|website=Official English Website for the City of Buenos Aires|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> Another Carlos Gardel Museum opened in 1999 in Valle Ed\u00e9n, an old farm site {{convert|23|km|abbr=on}} south of Tacuaremb\u00f3, Uruguay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.uruguay.com/uruguay_detail_675_carlos_gardel_museum.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303171246/http://english.uruguay.com/uruguay_detail_675_carlos_gardel_museum.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 March 2016 |title=Carlos Gardel Museum |publisher=Uruguay.com |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Uruguay produced a Gardel stamp calling him the \"immortal Tacuaremboan\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Feuding Uruguay, Argentina unite to preserve tango |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/latino/feuding-uruguay-argentina-unite-preserve-tango-article-1.412560?pgno=1 |page=2 |date=11 May 2009 |work=New York Daily News |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> On March 16, 2011, the United States Postal Service issued a set of five \"Latin Music Legends\" stamps including one picturing Carlos Gardel.<ref>USPS Postal News Release No. 11-024 (March 16, 2011)</ref>\n\n===In literature===\n[[Ant\u00f3nio Lobo Antunes]] wrote a novel entitled ''The Death of Carlos Gardel'', in which one of the characters believes that Gardel did not die in the plane crash in 1935.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nGardel appears as a fictionalized character in the play ''El d\u00eda que me quieras'' (1979) by the Venezuelan writer [[Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Cabrujas]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n===In film===\nIn the 1939 biopic ''[[The Life of Carlos Gardel]]'', he is portrayed by [[Hugo del Carril]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n''[[Doble o Nada]]'' starring Dario Grandinetti and Aitana S\u00e1nchez-Gij\u00f3n was released by Maverick in April 2003. It is a fictional story about a struggling Argentine tango singer who looks and sings like Gardel, and a woman admirer of Gardel, who encounters Franchi.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tango singers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquotelang|es}}\n{{wikisource-author}}\n{{Commons category|Carlos Gardel}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p78844}}\n* {{IMDb name|0306624}}\n* {{Cinenacional name|id=carlos-gardel|old_id=1813}}\n* [http://www.todotango.com/english/gardel/ Carlos Gardel] at Todotango.com\n* [http://soundsandcolours.com/articles/argentina/carlos-gardel-the-king-of-tango-8318/ Carlos Gardel: King of Tango] at Sounds and Colours\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardel, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Argentine singers]]\n[[Category:Argentine male singers]]\n[[Category:Burials at La Chacarita Cemetery]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to Argentina]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Male tango film actors]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures contract players]]\n[[Category:People with acquired Argentine citizenship]]\n[[Category:Tango singers]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in 1935]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "179.24.17.128", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life:Fixed wrong information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Gardel"}
{"title_page": "Cultural Survival", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n| name              = Cultural Survival\n| logo              = Culturalsurvival-logo.PNG\n| logo_size         = 250px\n| type              = [[Non-governmental organization]]\n| founded_date      = 1972\n| location          = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| key_people        = \n| area_served       = [[World|Worldwide]]\n| focus             = [[Indigenous rights]]\n| method            = \n| revenue           = [[United States dollar|US$]] 2,571,083 (2018)\n| num_members       = \n| homepage          = [http://www.culturalsurvival.org/ CulturalSurvival.org]\n}}\n\n{{Indigenous rights}}\n\n'''Cultural Survival''' (founded 1972) is a [[nonprofit organization|nonprofit group]] based in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]], which is dedicated to defending the [[human rights]] of [[indigenous peoples]].\n\n==History==\nCultural Survival's work is predicated on the United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples. Cultural Survival engage opportunities to leverage our experience and leadership in advocacy, media, public education, programs, and in providing platforms to amplify and empower the voices of Indigenous Peoples as they work to claim their rights to [[self-determination]], their lands, cultures, and precious ecosystems that are essential to the whole planet. Cultural Survival supports a movement of empowered Indigenous Peoples organizing their communities to engage the international processes, national policies and human rights bodies to respect, protect, and fulfill their rights. The organization is Indigenous-led and has a diverse board of directors bringing experiences from the Indigenous and non-Indigenous worlds to inform our perspectives and scope of work. Cultural Survival believes that vibrant and durable communities rest on the principles of self-determination, human rights, informed citizenry and [[access to information]], the [[freedom of expression]], and the right to organize and shape the future in a way consistent with one\u2019s tradition, language, culture and community \u2013 and we believe Indigenous Peoples have the power and solutions to solve many of today's problems when respected and empowered to do so.\n\nCultural Survival was founded by anthropologist [[David Maybury-Lewis]] and his wife, Pia,<ref>[http://www.credoreference.com/entry/routsca/maybury_lewis_david_h_p Credo Reference - Maybury-Lewis, David H.P. b. 1929, Hyderabad, Pakistan]</ref> in 1972, in response to the opening up of the Amazonian and South American hinterlands during the 1960s, and the drastic effects this had on Indigenous inhabitants. It has since worked with Indigenous communities in Asia, Africa, South America, North America, and Australia, becoming the leading US-based organization defending the rights of Indigenous Peoples around the world. Headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts, Cultural Survival has staff based in Canada, Panama, Nicaragua, Mexico, Guatemala, Nepal, and South Africa. Cultural Survival holds a four-star rating from [[Charity Navigator]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=10875 |title=Cultural Survival |publisher=Charity Navigator |accessdate=8 December 2012 |archivedate=9 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ClvCveCc?url=http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=10875 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Mission and Vision==\nCultural Survival advocates for Indigenous Peoples' rights and supports Indigenous communities\u2019 self-determination, cultures and political resilience since 1972. Cultural Survival envisions a future that respects and honors Indigenous Peoples' inherent rights and dynamic cultures, deeply and richly interwoven in lands, languages, spiritual traditions, and artistic expression, rooted in self-determination and self-governance.\n\n==Programmatic Work==\nSince 1972, Cultural Survival has partnered with Indigenous communities to advance Indigenous Peoples' rights and cultures worldwide. The core of our efforts rest on the principles of supporting, amplifying efforts and raising awareness of self-determination for Indigenous communities. Cultural Survival employs a participatory, rights-based approach to our relationships that respects and strengthens Indigenous rights while honoring traditional Indigenous worldviews and lifeways. Our programs work to inform, create resources for, support access to information, bolster freedom of expression, and assist Indigenous communities to organize and shape their futures in ways consistent with their traditions, languages, cultures. Cultural Survival publicizes Indigenous Peoples' issues through our award-winning Cultural Survival Quarterly; it mounts on the ground campaigns and other advocacy efforts to stop environmental destruction and abuses of Indigenous Peoples' rights, always at the community\u2019s invitation. Headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts, Cultural Survival has staff based in Guatemala, Panama, Mexico, Nicaragua, Nepal, Canada, and South Africa. Cultural Survival also holds consultative status with the United Nations Economic Social and Cultural Council since 2005. \n\n==Publications==\n*''Cultural Survival Quarterly'' magazine has covered Indigenous rights issues for over 40 years. Each issue includes feature articles focused on themes of concern to Indigenous peoples, as well as news pieces, interviews, and book reviews. All of the authors are Indigenous or are professionals who work closely with Indigenous Peoples.{{citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Friends of Peoples Close to Nature]]\n*[[Survival International]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cs.org/}}\n\n{{Indigenous rights footer}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Indigenous rights organizations in North America]]\n[[Category:Anthropology organizations]]\n[[Category:Ethnology]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name   = Cultural Survival\n| logo   = Culturalsurvival-logo.PNG\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type   = [[Non-governmental organization]]\n| founded_date      = 1972\n| location          = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[United States]]\n| key_people        = \n| area_served       = [[World]]wide\n| focus             = [[Indigenous rights]]\n| method            = \n| revenue           = [[United States dollar|US$]] 2,571,083 (2018)\n| num_members       = \n| homepage          = [http://www.culturalsurvival.org/ culturalsurvival.org]\n}}\n{{Indigenous rights}}\n'''Cultural Survival''' (founded 1972) is a [[Non-profit organization|nonprofit group]] based in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States|US]], which is dedicated to defending the [[human rights]] of [[Indigenous Peoples]].\n\n==History==\nCultural Survival's work is predicated on the United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples. Cultural Survival engage opportunities to leverage our experience and leadership in advocacy, media, public education, programs, and in providing platforms to amplify and empower the voices of Indigenous Peoples as they work to claim their rights to [[self-determination]], their lands, cultures, and precious ecosystems that are essential to the whole planet. Cultural Survival supports a movement of empowered Indigenous Peoples organizing their communities to engage the international processes, national policies and human rights bodies to respect, protect, and fulfill their rights. The organization is Indigenous-led and has a diverse board of directors bringing experiences from the Indigenous and non-Indigenous worlds to inform our perspectives and scope of work. Cultural Survival believes that vibrant and durable communities rest on the principles of self-determination, human rights, informed citizenry and [[access to information]], the [[freedom of expression]], and the right to organize and shape the future in a way consistent with one\u2019s tradition, language, culture and community \u2013 and we believe Indigenous Peoples have the power and solutions to solve many of today's problems when respected and empowered to do so.\n\nCultural Survival was founded by anthropologist [[David Maybury-Lewis]] and his wife, Pia,<ref>[http://www.credoreference.com/entry/routsca/maybury_lewis_david_h_p Credo Reference - Maybury-Lewis, David H.P. b. 1929, Hyderabad, Pakistan]</ref> in 1972, in response to the opening up of the Amazonian and South American hinterlands during the 1960s, and the drastic effects this had on Indigenous inhabitants. It has since worked with Indigenous communities in Asia, Africa, South America, North America, and Australia, becoming the leading US-based organization defending the rights of Indigenous Peoples around the world. Headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts, Cultural Survival has staff based in Canada, Panama, Nicaragua, Mexico, Guatemala, Nepal, and South Africa. Cultural Survival holds a four-star rating from [[Charity Navigator]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=10875 |title=Cultural Survival |publisher=Charity Navigator |accessdate=8 December 2012 |archivedate=9 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ClvCveCc?url=http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=10875 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Mission and Vision==\nCultural Survival advocates for Indigenous Peoples' rights and supports Indigenous communities\u2019 self-determination, cultures and political resilience since 1972. Cultural Survival envisions a future that respects and honors Indigenous Peoples' inherent rights and dynamic cultures, deeply and richly interwoven in lands, languages, spiritual traditions, and artistic expression, rooted in self-determination and self-governance.\n\n==Programmatic Work==\nSince 1972, Cultural Survival has partnered with Indigenous communities to advance Indigenous Peoples' rights and cultures worldwide. The core of our efforts rest on the principles of supporting, amplifying efforts and raising awareness of self-determination for Indigenous communities. Cultural Survival employs a participatory, rights-based approach to our relationships that respects and strengthens Indigenous rights while honoring traditional Indigenous worldviews and lifeways. Our programs work to inform, create resources for, support access to information, bolster freedom of expression, and assist Indigenous communities to organize and shape their futures in ways consistent with their traditions, languages, cultures. Cultural Survival publicizes Indigenous Peoples' issues through our award-winning Cultural Survival Quarterly; it mounts on the ground campaigns and other advocacy efforts to stop environmental destruction and abuses of Indigenous Peoples' rights, always at the community\u2019s invitation. Headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts, Cultural Survival has staff based in Guatemala, Panama, Mexico, Nicaragua, Nepal, Canada, and South Africa. Cultural Survival also holds consultative status with the United Nations Economic Social and Cultural Council since 2005. \n\n==Publications==\n\n*''Cultural Survival Quarterly'' magazine has covered Indigenous rights issues for over 40 years. Each issue includes feature articles focused on themes of concern to Indigenous peoples, as well as news pieces, interviews, and book reviews. All of the authors are Indigenous or are professionals who work closely with Indigenous Peoples.{{citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Friends of Peoples Close to Nature]]\n*[[Survival International]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cs.org}}\n\n{{Indigenous rights footer}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Indigenous rights organizations in North America]]\n[[Category:Anthropology organizations]]\n[[Category:Ethnology]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cultural_Survival"}
