{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon\n| width =\n| image         = File:Coronavirus responses in Portland Oregon.jpeg\n| image_size    = \n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Sign on a storefront in [[Portland, Oregon]], noting a temporary closure due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing coronavirus pandemic]]\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)\n| virus_strain = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome<br />coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2)\n| location = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| first_case =\n| arrival_date = <!-- or | dates = -->\n| date = \n| origin =\n| type =\n| confirmed_cases =\n| active_cases =\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths =\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|https://beta.portland.gov/novel-coronavirus-covid-19}}\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon''', is an ongoing viral pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). Efforts to prevent the virus spreading include event postponements and cancellations, and facility closures.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus disease 2019|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2}}\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oregon}}\n[[File:Ghost Hug chalk writing on Hawthorne during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Chalk writing on a sidewalk in southeast Portland during the pandemic]]\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] is an ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The outbreak started in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]] province, [[China]], in December 2019. The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declared the outbreak to be a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] on 30 January 2020 and a pandemic on 11 March 2020.\n\nAs of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|conround|editlink=|ref=no}} cases of COVID-19 have been reported in more than 200 countries and territories, resulting in more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|dround|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} More than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recround|editlink=|ref=no}} people have recovered.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}}\n\nThe pandemic was first confirmed to have spread to the United States in January 2020. Cases have been confirmed in all fifty U.S. states, [[Washington, D.C.]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=\"mariana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=samoanews.com|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|03|31|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases in the world and ranks third in the number of total deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The pandemic was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of Oregon on February 28, 2020.\n\n==Cases==\nOregon's first presumptive case was announced in Portland on February 28, 2020. Governor [[Kate Brown]] spoke and the director of the [[Oregon Health Authority]] confirmed someone from [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] who worked at Forest Hills Elementary School in [[Lake Oswego, Oregon|Lake Oswego]] was being treated at [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]]'s [[Kaiser Westside Medical Center]]. The [[Lake Oswego School District]] closed the school for cleaning.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |title=State officials announce first presumptive case of coronavirus in Oregon |url=https://www.kptv.com/news/state-officials-announce-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus-in-oregon/article_6ac26688-5a93-11ea-a0af-d346d4e06ef0.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[KPTV]] |date=February 28, 2020 |location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref><ref name=\"firstabc\">{{cite news |last1=Selsky |first1=Andrew |title=Oregon has 1st coronavirus case: elementary school employee |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/oregon-1st-coronavirus-case-elementary-school-employee-69298619 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |via=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> The first case in [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] and fifteenth in Oregon was confirmed on March 10; the patient was treatment at the [[Veterans Affairs Medical Center (Oregon)|Veterans Affairs Medical Center]].<ref name=\"case15\">{{cite news |title=Oregon confirms 15th coronavirus case in state |url=https://www.registerguard.com/news/20200310/oregon-confirms-15th-coronavirus-case-in-state |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Register-Guard]] |date=March 10, 2020 |location=Eugene, Oregon}}</ref> An employee who worked at the [[Wells Fargo Center (Portland, Oregon)|Wells Fargo Center]] tested positive on March 14, prompting building tenant [[Davis Wright Tremaine]] to close offices in Portland.<ref name=\"skyscraper\">{{cite news |last1=Rogoway |first1=Mike |title=Coronavirus case linked to downtown Portland skyscraper |url=https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/456350-372216-coronavirus-case-linked-to-downtown-portland-skyscraper-pwoff |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> More than 30 people in the Portland metropolitan area tested positive by April 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/strong-evidence-seen-that-oregons-coronavirus-restrictions-are-working.html |title=\u2018Strong evidence\u2019 seen that Oregon\u2019s coronavirus restrictions are working |website=The Oregonian |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n{{Main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Multnomah County Library Northwest branch with closure notice during 2020 coronavirus epidemic.jpg|thumb|left|Closure notice posted at the [[Northwest Library]] on March 16, 2020]]\n\nOn March 13, the [[Portland Police Bureau]] announced a reduction of in-person responses to reduce virus transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kobi5.com/news/portland-police-reduce-in-person-responses-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-123900/|title=Portland police reduce in-person responses amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|website=KOBI-TV NBC5 / KOTI-TV NBC2|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/487984-police-nationwide-ask-criminals-to-halt-activity|title=Police nationwide ask criminals to halt activity during coronavirus outbreak|first=Justine|last=Coleman|date=March 17, 2020|website=TheHill}}</ref> [[Multnomah County Library]] closed all branch libraries and [[Portland Parks and Recreation]] (PPR) closed arts and community centers, sports facilities, and swimming pools, based on recommendations issued by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], [[Multnomah County Health Department]], and the Oregon Health Authority. PPR canceled athletic programs and indoor activities at community centers, but did not close golf courses, natural areas, parks, playgrounds, or trails, or cancel outdoor events for less than 250 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/covid--closures-multnomah-county-libraries-some-portland-parks-rec/article_d56dbd54-659a-11ea-a9dc-637432f6280c.html|title=COVID-19 closures: Multnomah County libraries, some Portland Parks & Rec facilities shut down|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Multnomah County Chair Deborah Kafoury announced plans to add as many as 400 beds for county residents affected by the pandemic requiring shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/multnomah-county-to-add-hundreds-of-homeless-shelter-beds-within-the-week-for-people-with-symptoms-of-coronavirus.html|title=Multnomah County to add hundreds of homeless shelter beds within the week to help with coronavirus|first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 17, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> 120 beds were made available at the PPR-owned [[Charles Jordan Community Center]] in north Portland on March 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/first-coronavirus-related-emergency-homeless-shelter-to-open-in-north-portland.html|title=First coronavirus-related emergency homeless shelter to open in North Portland|first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 19, 2020| work=The Oregonian}}</ref> [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]]'s [[Oregon Convention Center]], unable to host events since March 12, was converted into a temporary shelter with 130\u2013140 beds. The Joint Office of Homeless Services, a collaboration between Metro and Multnomah County, hoped to open additional beds for healthy individuals as overflow from existing shelters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-convention-center-shelter/283-3f46becb-f2fa-4865-9cc1-65b35c741085|title=Oregon Convention Center to become temporary coronavirus-related homeless shelter|publisher=[[KGW]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/homeless-will-find-refuge-at-oregon-convention-center/|title=Homeless will find refuge at Oregon Convention Center|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=[[KOIN (TV)|KOIN]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Trucks normally used by Multnomah Country Library and for animal control were repurposed to assist with the convention center conversion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/tape-and-two-hours-to-transform-oregon-convention-center-into-coronavirus-homeless-shelter.html|title=Tape and 2 hours to transform Oregon Convention Center into coronavirus homeless shelter|first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 21, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 22, Mayor [[Ted Wheeler]] said he was prepared to issue a [[stay-at-home order]] for Portland residents if Governor Brown would not issue a similar order for Oregon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/wheeler-to-brown-issue-statewide-stay-at-home-order/|title=Wheeler to Brown: Issue statewide stay-at-home order|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/mayor-wheeler-on-stay-at-home-order-im-ready-to-act-for-portland-tomorrow|title=Mayor Wheeler on stay-at-home order: 'I'm ready to act for Portland tomorrow'|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=[[KATU]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The governor was also pressured by 25 Portland-area mayors, Metro's council, multiple county chairs, and other elected and health officials. She issued an executive order on March 23 requiring home [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] for Oregonians, with some exceptions, and to practice [[social distancing]]. Violators may be punished with 30 days in jail and fines as high as $1,250 as a class C [[misdemeanor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-stay-at-home-order-coronavirus-covid-19-kate-brown/|title=Gov. Kate Brown Issues Order Directing Oregonians To 'Stay Home'|first=Dirk|last=VanderHart|date=March 2, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The Portland Police Bureau confirmed criminal citations were a \"last resort measure\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/23/portland-police-can-now-issue-criminal-citations-to-those-who-violate-browns-stay-at-home-order/|title=Portland Police May Now Issue Criminal Citations to Anyone Who Violates Brown\u2019s Stay at Home Order|date=March 23, 2020 |first1=Tess |last1=Riski |newspaper=Willamette Week}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n{{Main|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Hand sanitizer and gloves sold out due to Coronavirus 10 57 26 366000.jpeg|thumb|right|Empty [[latex glove]] shelves at a [[Rite Aid]] store in [[downtown Portland]]]]\n\n[[Delta Air Lines]] reduced flights between Portland and Japan. United Airlines cut 4 of 20 flights from Portland as well as one from Eugene. [[Sun Country Airlines]] reduced flights between Portland and Honolulu, Las Vegas, and San Francisco.<ref name=Outlook>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-darkens-oregons-economic-outlook-but-impacts-are-muted-for-now.html |title=Coronavirus darkens Oregon's economic outlook, but impacts are muted -- for now |first=Mike |last= Rogoway |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchool closures and event cancellations prompted people to stock up on groceries. Long lines were seen at grocery stores and food pantries throughout the Portland metropolitan area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-grocery-stores-and-food-pantries-busy-as-covid-/article_67560a58-6656-11ea-b7d7-c3c87e0e2492.html|title=Portland grocery stores and food pantries busy as COVID-19 closures begin|first=John|last=Hendricks|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Local [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] dispensaries saw an increased demand as customers stocked up in case stores were forced to close temporarily.<ref name=Open>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-portland-coronavirus-covid-19-whats-open/|title=Life In The Time Of Coronavirus: What's Still Open In Oregon?|first=Donald|last=Orr|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[Oregon Liquor Control Commission]] (OLCC) permitted stores to operate via curbside pick-up and home delivery temporarily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/weve-been-having-420-every-day-for-the-last-2-weeks-oregon-pot-shops-see-spike-in-business-with-new-curbside-delivery/283-163e563c-a5e4-4b2a-87e1-76578a607346|title=\u2018We\u2019ve been having 4/20 every day\u2019: Oregon pot shops see spike in business with new curbside delivery|website=KGW}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/at-home-because-of-the-coronavirus-shutdown-heres-who-delivers-cannabis-products-in-portland.html|title=At home because of the coronavirus shutdown? Here's who delivers cannabis products in Portland|first=Lizzy|last=Acker|date=March 25, 2020|website=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186115/oregon-cannabis-dispensaries-now-allowed-to-offer-curbside-pickup|title=Oregon Cannabis Dispensaries Now Allowed to Offer Curbside Pickup|first1=Wm Steven|last1=Humphrey|date=March 23, 2020|work=Portland Mercury}}</ref>\n\n===Business closures and event cancellations===\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 15.jpg|thumb|left|upright|People practicing social distancing while waiting to enter [[New Seasons Market]] in the [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]] neighborhood]]\n\n[[Adidas]] closed offices at Montgomery Park and Portland Village after two employees had close content with someone who tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/nba/adidas-closes-north-american-headquarters-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Adidas closes North American headquarters amid COVID-19 pandemic|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Powell's Books]] five stores closed,<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/powells-books-closes-as-coronavirus-spreads-in-portland-metro|title=Powell's Books closes as coronavirus spreads in Portland metro|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and laid off most staff members.<ref name=Open/> [[Portland Incubator Experiment]] canceled PIE Demo Day; the March 19 event scheduled to be held at [[Revolution Hall]] was held online.<ref name=Stein/> On March 25, [[Daimler Trucks North America]] shut down a plant on Swan Island until April 6.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/daimler-trucks-shutting-down-portland-plant-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Daimler Trucks shutting down Portland plant amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike |last=Rogoway |date=March 25, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref> Portland-based companies [[Puppet (company)|Puppet]] and [[Vacasa]] laid off employees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2020/03/portland-marketing-technology-startup-opal-lays-off-20-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Portland technology companies lay off dozens amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n\n[[Oaks Amusement Park]] and the [[Oaks Park Roller Skating Rink]], the [[Oregon Historical Society]], the [[Oregon Zoo]], [[Portland Children's Museum]],<ref name=Stein>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/event-cancellationspostponements-due-to-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=Events canceled in Oregon over the next months|first=Rosemarie |last=Stein |date=March 10, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref> and [[Portland Japanese Garden]] closed as well.<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/list-portland-area-museums-attractions-closed-amid-coronavirus-response/|title=LIST: Portland area museums, attractions closed amid coronavirus response|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> As of March 19, the [[Portland Art Museum]] and [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] are closed through March 31 and mid April, respectively.<ref name=Open/> The [[Crystal Ballroom (Portland, Oregon)|Crystal Ballroom]] and [[Hawthorne Theatre]] canceled or postponed planned shows through mid April.<ref name=Open/> The [[City Club of Portland]] canceled activities.<ref name=MCL>{{Cite news|last=Monahan|first=Rachel|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/13/multnomah-county-library-closed-as-of-today-in-response-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Multnomah County Library Closed in Response to the Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|work=[[Willamette Week]]|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The [[Portland Rose Festival]] has postponed annual events, including the [[Starlight Parade]], indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/2020/03/19/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed-indefinitely/|title=The Portland Rose Festival Has Been Postponed Indefinitely|date=March 19, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/entertainment/2020/03/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed.html|title=The 2020 Portland Rose Festival has been postponed due to coronavirus crisis|first1=Rosemarie |last1=Stein |first2=Kjerstin |last2=Gabrielson |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Herbal Products Association]]'s Hemp-CBD Congress, scheduled for mid April at the [[Benson Hotel]], was canceled.<ref name=Stein/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/09/28113766/coronavirus-and-cannabis-how-pot-is-impacted-by-a-pandemic |title=Coronavirus and Cannabis: How Pot Is Impacted by a Pandemic |first1=Josh |last1=Jardine  |date=March 9, 2020 |newspaper=[[Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[Road Runners Club of America]]'s annual convention, slated to be held at the [[Hilton Portland Hotel]] during March 19\u201322, was also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> A conference on [[affordable housing]], climate, and community stability featuring [[Julian Castro]] during April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[TechfestNW]] was to be held at [[Portland State University]] during April 2\u20133, but was rescheduled for August 6\u20137. April 11's Cider Rite of Spring was rescheduled for November, and Design Week Festival was moved from the week starting April 18 to August 1\u20138. The arts and technology festival [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO]] scheduled for September has been canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[Pride Northwest]]'s annual [[pride parade]] has been postponed, and the Portland Retro Gaming Expo has been canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186244/todays-coronavirus-news-roundup-brown-issues-stay-home-order-dems-slam-gop-stimulus-bill-and-trump-keeps-getting-in-the-way|title=Today's Coronavirus News Roundup: Brown Issues \"Stay Home\" Order, Dems Slam GOP Stimulus Bill, and Trump Keeps Getting in the Way|date=March 23, 2020|work=[ Portland Mercury}}</ref> The [[Waterfront Blues Festival]], slated for July 2\u20135, was canceled on March 25.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/waterfront-blues-festival-canceled-for-2020-will-return-in-2021.html|title=Waterfront Blues Festival canceled for 2020, will return in 2021|first=Samantha|last=Swindler|date=March 24, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/music/2020/03/24/the-waterfront-blues-festival-has-been-canceled-due-to-the-pandemic/|title=The Waterfront Blues Festival Has Been Canceled Due to the Pandemic|date=March 24, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/organizers-cancel-waterfront-blues-festival-over-coronavirus-concerns|title=Organizers cancel Waterfront Blues Festival over coronavirus concerns|author=KATU Staff|date=March 24, 2020|website=KATU}}</ref>\n\nWhile cheer and dance competitions were still being held at the Oregon Convention Center in early March,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/crowds-gather-at-convention-center-despite-virus-concerns/|title=Crowds gather at convention center despite virus concerns|date=March 7, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> many events planned to be hosted at the venue were canceled. On February 5, the Materials Show scheduled for February 12\u201313 was canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-trade-show-canceled-over-coronavirus-concerns/article_28d3fde8-4889-11ea-bcd6-8bb625985644.html|title=Portland trade show canceled over coronavirus concerns|date=February 5, 2020|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://q13fox.com/2020/02/05/portland-convention-rescheduled-over-coronavirus-fears/|title=Portland convention rescheduled over coronavirus fears|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Gem Faire and the Multnomah County Democrats' annual Celsi Celebration slated for the weekend of March 21 were also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 6, organizers of the Go West Summit, an international travel conference for March 24\u201327 expecting approximately 800 people, was postponed.<ref name=Hotels>{{Cite news|last=Iboshi|first=Kyle|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-hotels-see-significant-room-cancellations-travel-conference-postponed/283-6d3b08c3-7a8a-4b56-a65c-bac4919cd73d|title=Portland hotels see 'significant' room cancellations; travel conference postponed|date=March 6, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The Oregon Dental Association's annual Oregon Dental Conference for April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 9, the Burning Cat event being organized by the [[Exploding Kittens (company)|company]] behind the card game [[Exploding Kittens]] for May was canceled.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/09/event-canceled-at-oregon-convention-center-amid.html|title=Event canceled at Oregon Convention Center|last=|first=|date=March 9, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, restrictions prompted the closures of amusement parks, barber shops, bowling alleys, gyms, hair and nail salons, malls, spas, and theaters.<ref name=Lillard>{{Cite web|last=Nemec|first=Andrew|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/blazers/2020/03/damian-lillard-joins-nba-instagram-encourages-social-distancing-staying-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Damian Lillard joins NBA Instagram, encourages social distancing, staying home amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 23, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n\n====Film industry and the performing arts====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n{{multiple image\n | width = 200\n | image1 = Bagdad Theater, Portland Oregon, during coronavirus closure.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | image2 = Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus .jpeg\n | alt2 = \n | footer = [[Bagdad Theatre]] (left) and [[Laurelhurst Theater]] (right) with marquee messages acknowledging closures because of the pandemic  \n}}\n\nLocal movie theaters were forced to close temporarily. Among them were [[Cinema 21]] and [[Laurelhurst Theater]],<ref name=Venues/> which was unable to continue operating with capacity limits and social distancing measures, despite efforts.<ref name=Open/> On March 13, the [[Hollywood Theatre (Portland, Oregon)|Hollywood Theatre]] confirmed plans to close from March 14 to April 8; previously, the theater was limiting capacity to 250 people per Oregon's ban on events and other social gatherings.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/movies/2020/03/13/portlands-hollywood-theatre-will-close-until-april-8/|title=Portland's Hollywood Theatre Will Close Until April 8|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Movie Madness Video]], a [[video rental shop]] and [[history of film]] museum, closed and waived late fees on rentals.<ref name=Open/> Cinema 21 later allowed people to stream independent films at home.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cook|first=Katherine|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/entertainment/local-theaters-let-customers-stream-independent-films-from-home/283-d3c31d70-3985-4ed4-8047-284195efcc54|title=Local theaters let customers stream independent films from home|date=March 30, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=Apr 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]] and Brunish Theatre at [[Antoinette Hatfield Hall]] closed,<ref name=Venues>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-response-public-venues-omsi-childrens-museum-ohs-close-for-2-weeks.html|title=Oregon closures: Libraries, recreation centers, museums, ski resorts, zoo, retailers|first=Rosemarie |last=Stein |date=March 13, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref> forcing the [[Oregon Symphony]] to cancel performances.<ref name=Rogoway/> Initially, the symphony canceled performances between March 13 and April 6.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/12/oregon-symphony-cancels-march-early-april-shows.html|title=Oregon Symphony cancels March, Early April shows|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> 76 musicians, two conductors, and 19 staff members were laid off, and the organization's [[President (corporate title)|president]] and [[chief executive officer]] has submitted an appeal for funding to Governor Brown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-symphony-lays-off-orchestra-conductors-and-staff-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html|title=Oregon Symphony lays off orchestra, conductors and staff amid coronavirus crisis|first=Nathan |last=Rizzo |date=March 20, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Portland Center Stage]] canceled productions for eight weeks (through April 8) and furloughed 78 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/radio/article/coronavirus-fears-affect-oregons-biggest-arts-organizations/|title=Coronavirus Closures Endanger Oregon's Most Prominent Arts Organizations|first1=Steven|last1=Tonthat|first2=Eric|last2=Slade|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Portland Opera]] canceled March 20\u201328 performances of ''[[Bajazet (opera)|Bajazet]]'' at Antoinette Hatfield Hall's Newmark Theatre.<ref name=Stein/> The arts center [[Disjecta]] canceled or postponed activities.<ref name=Stein/> The [[Northwest Film Center]] closed and the Portland International Film Festival was canceled.<ref name=Open/> [[The Old Church (Portland, Oregon)|The Old Church]] has postponed concerts through April 8, forcing [[Chamber Music Northwest]] to reschedule some performances.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n====Food service and restaurant industry====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n[[File:Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus16 13 59 290000.jpeg|thumb|left|Sign noting [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]]'s closure]]\n\nThe city's restaurant industry was \"completely obliterated\" by the state's bar and restaurant ban.<ref name=Rogoway>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-brings-oregon-a-sudden-economic-catastrophe-the-worst-week-ever.html|title=Coronavirus brings Oregon a sudden economic catastrophe: 'The worst week ever'|first=Mike |last=Rogoway |date=March 22, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref> Governor Brown banned in-house consumption across Oregon, effective March 17. Some restaurants closed entirely, while others implemented [[food delivery]] and [[take-out]] operations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/responding-to-coronavirus-pandemic-vegan-fine-dining-restaurant-farm-spirit-upscale-steakhouse-el-gaucho-will-close-temporarily.html |title=Portland restaurants close dining rooms; some offer delivery|first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 13, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Closures>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/13/21178995/covid-19-coronavirus-closures-portland|title=A Number of Restaurants Once Open for Takeout and Delivery Have Closed List Last Week|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 13, 2020|website=[[Eater (website)|Eater Portland]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> [[Acadia: A New Orleans Bistro]], [[Doug Fir Lounge]], [[Ken's Artisan Pizza]], [[Le Bistro Montage]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/portland-restaurants-closed-due-to-coronavirus.html |title=Here are all the Portland restaurants to close or embrace takeout, delivery-only service |first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 14, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Le Pigeon]], [[Nostrana (restaurant)|Nostrana]], [[Olympia Provisions]], [[Pok Pok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/25/21194167/pok-pok-closed|title=The Pok Pok Empire Closes Indefinitely in Wake of Coronavirus Crisis|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 25, 2020|website=Eater Portland}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/how-to-make-pok-poks-fish-sauce-wings-at-home.html|title=With Pok Pok restaurants closed, here's how to make those famous fish sauce wings at home|first=Michael|last=Russell|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref> and [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]] all closed.<ref name=Closures/> [[Hot Lips Pizza]], [[Oven and Shaker]], and [[Sizzle Pie]] continued pizza pickup and delivery service, as of March 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/27/21194686/where-to-find-a-pizza-during-the-restaurant-shutdown|title=Where to Find a Pizza During the Restaurant Shutdown|first=Sam|last=Hill|date=March 27, 2020|website=Eater Portland}}</ref> [[Shine Distillery and Grill]] began producing [[hand sanitizer]] from alcohol for customers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2020/03/19/oregon-shine-distillery-making-hand-sanitizer-coronavirus-bts-ctn-vpx.cnn|title=Oregon distillery is making its own in-house hand sanitizer and giving it away|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Andi|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/10/a-portland-distillery-is-making-its-own-hand-cleaner-in-the-wake-of-coronavirus/|title=A Portland Distillery Is Making Its Own Hand Cleaner in the Wake of Coronavirus|date=March 10, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-distillery-makes-hand-sanitizer-to-give-to-customers/article_c79023bc-6292-11ea-832b-e3a4b8d06435.html|title=Portland distillery makes hand sanitizer to give to customers|first=Audrey|last=Weil|publisher=KPTV}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/11/21174997/shine-distillery-hand-cleaning-solution|title=North Portland's Shine Distillery Is Giving Away House-Made, 80-Percent-Alcohol Hand 'Cleaner'|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 11, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The website 'PDX2Go' was created to track businesses still accepting orders, and some food carts continued to operate.<ref name=Open/>\n\nTwelve of 27 laid off [[Crush Bar]] employees staged a protest and accused the owner of \"[breaking] the law by denying their use of accrued sick hours to cover lost wages\". The demonstration was supposed to last for 24 hours but was stopped by police after an hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/17/21184325/crush-bar-sit-in-layoffs-covid-19|title=Crush Bar Employees Staged Sit-In After Mass Layoffs [Updated]|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 17, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[strip club]] Lucky Devil Lounge continued to offer a full menu with home delivery service by \"scantily clad strippers\" under the business operation Boober Eats.<ref name=Lucky>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-strip-club-forced-to-close-so-dancers-now-do-delivery.html|title=Portland strip club forced to close, so dancers now do delivery|first=Samantha |last=Swindler |date=March 22, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/17/a-portland-strip-club-has-started-a-meal-delivery-service-where-dancers-bring-food-directly-to-your-door-to-your-home/|title=A Portland Strip Club Has Started a Meal Delivery Service Where Dancers Bring Food Directly to Your Door|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/strippers-staff-boober-eats-delivery-service-during-coronavirus-lockdown/|title=Strippers staff 'Boober Eats' delivery service during coronavirus lockdown|first=Hannah|last=Sparks|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Approximately 25 strippers have participated; dancers are driven and protected by security guards, armed with gloves, masks, and hand sanitizer,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/boober-eats-lucky-devil-lounge-strip-club-covid-19-coronavirus-quarantine-971544/|title=With Clubs Closed for COVID-19, Strippers in Portland, Oregon, Take to Topless Food Delivery|first1=E. J.|last1=Dickson|first2=E. J.|last2=Dickson|date=March 23, 2020|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and touching by customers is not allowed.<ref name=Lucky/>\n\n====Hospitality industry====\nThe [[hospitality industry]] also experienced a wave of guest cancellations followed by a decline in bookings.<ref name=Hotels/> The [[Jupiter Hotel (Portland, Oregon)|Jupiter Hotel]] laid off half its staff by March 18 after daily occupancy rates fell to 7\u201320 percent.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-hotels-lay-off-workers-question-survival-after-wave-of-coronavirus-cancellations.html |title=Oregon hotels lay off workers, question futures after wave of coronavirus cancellations |first=Jamie |last=Goldberg |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Jupiter partnered with Multnomah County to use the hotel's 81 rooms as a temporary homeless shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pamplinmedia.com/go/42-news/459054-373887-portlands-jupiter-hotel-becomes-coronavirus-shelter-for-medically-fragile-homeless-people|title=Portland's Jupiter Hotel becomes coronavirus shelter for medically fragile homeless people|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/local/portland-hotel-donates-rooms-to-help-homeless-with-coronavirus-symptoms-stay-in-quarantine|title=Portland hotel donates rooms to help homeless with coronavirus symptoms stay in quarantine|first=KATU|last=Staff|date=March 26, 2020|website=KATU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hanson|first=Nate |url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/homeless/jupiter-hotel-homeless-shelter-portland-coronavirus/283-370d4b13-f607-4460-98ed-6a6d5465d83d|title=Jupiter Hotel in Portland to become homeless shelter during coronavirus pandemic|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=KGW}}</ref> [[The Nines (hotel)|The Nines]] suspended hotel and restaurant operations on March 19, effective March 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-luxury-hotel-nines-suspends-services-due-to-covid/article_6b47548a-6a40-11ea-adb7-4f0a8a298283.html|title=Portland luxury hotel Nines suspends services due to COVID-19|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Impact on professional sports====\n[[File:Providence Park box office notice - closed due to COVID-19 epidemic, 3-16-2020.jpg|thumb|Box office closure sign at [[Providence Park]], home of the [[Portland Timbers]] and [[Portland Thorns FC]], on March 16, 2020]]\n\nFollowing season suspensions by the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/mls-suspends-season-due-to-coronavirus-delaying-timbers-season|title=MLS suspends season due to coronavirus, delaying Timbers season|first=Evan|last=Schreiber|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] and [[Portland Timbers]] canceled games.<ref name=Rogoway/> The Trail Blazers and Timbers games averaged approximately 19,000 and 25,000 people at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/service-industry-portland-coronavirus-nba-mls-moda-center/|title=Portland Service Industry Reeling And Uncertain With NBA, MLS On Hold|first1=Troy|last1=Brynelson|first2=Bradley W.|last2=Parks|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> MLS initially announced a 30-day suspension, when the Timbers were scheduled to play at [[Providence Park]] five times between March 12 and mid April.<ref name=NBC>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/portland-timbers/breaking-mls-suspends-season-due-coronavirus|title=BREAKING: MLS suspends season due to coronavirus|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The soccer league extended the suspension to eight weeks on March 19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/major-league-soccer-extends-season-postponement-for-another-month/283-d59a5f0d-0416-4929-893e-73399e61476f|title=Major League Soccer extends season postponement for another month|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[Portland Thorns FC]]'s pre-season tournament slated for March 29 \u2013 April 4 was canceled on March 12, shortly before the [[National Women's Soccer League]] canceled pre-season games across the league.<ref name=Thorns>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2020/03/portland-thorns-cancel-preseason-tournament-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Thorns cancel preseason tournament amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Jamie|last=Goldberg|date=March 12, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref> Timbers and Thorns tickets will be valid for rescheduled matches, as of March 12.<ref name=Thorns/> On March 17, the Timbers and Thorns announced part-time workers would still receive compensation for canceled games, among other community initiatives.<ref>{{Cite news|author=KGW Staff|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/portland-timbers-thorns-to-pay-part-time-workers/283-ae77774b-161a-4b19-9699-266bd9ef8e26|title=Portland Timbers, Thorns to pay part-time workers for games missed during coronavirus outbreak|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Damian Lillard]] encouraged fans to remain at home and practice social distancing. He said on the NBA's [[Instagram]] account on March 23, \"I've been washing my hands, social distancing \u2014 keep your space. Don't join in crowds, stay in small groups. It'd be best to stay in the house. I hope everybody is stocked up on everything they need so they can stay safe. Do everything the way we've been asked to help this pass faster. Like I said, ya'll stay safe, ya'll be good, man.\"<ref name=Lillard/>\n\n==Impact on education==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 05.jpg|thumb|Sign noting [[Reed College]]'s closure]]\n\nGovernor Brown initially closed schools all K\u201312 schools through March 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/portland-metro-school-district-tigard-tualatin-lake-oswego-coronavirus-board-meeting-emergency-covid-students/|title=Brown orders all K-12 schools closed through March|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A four-week extension was added; students are scheduled to return on April 28. [[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools]] designated 15 buildings as sites for student meal distributions, and has considered providing 45,000 devices to students for [[distance education]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-public-schools-begins-plans-for-6-week-closure.html|title=Portland Public Schools begins plans for 6-week closure|first=Eder|last=Campuzano|date=March 18, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> High school and college graduation ceremonies were canceled.<ref name=Rogoway/>\n\nAll Multnomah County Library branches were closed on March 13.<ref name=MCL/> The library system waived late fees and continued to provide public [[Wi-Fi]].<ref name=Open/>\n\nStudents at [[Oregon Health & Science University]] and the University of Portland began offering childcare and errand services for local health care professionals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-area-healthcare-workers-can-request-free-childcare-other-support-from-local-medical-and-nursing-students.html|title=Portland-area healthcare workers can request free childcare, other support from local medical and nursing students|first=Amy|last=Wang|date=March 21, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Universities and collegiate sports===\n[[Portland State University]] canceled in-person final exams,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/schools/2020/03/12/portland-state-university-cancels-in-person-final-exams-moves-spring-classes-online/|title=Portland State University Cancels In-Person Final Exams, Moves Spring Classes Online|last=Mesh|first=Aaron|last2=|first2=|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=|first3=}}</ref> and eliminated in-person classes for the spring term, opting for distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-state-university-will-not-resume-in-person-classes-this-spring.html|title=Portland State will not resume in-person classes this spring|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|date=March 19, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[University of Portland]] moved to online instruction and canceled all sports games and practices for the spring term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/university-of-oregon-classes-remotely-coronavirus/283-b5b5abc3-463f-442a-abc6-964fb9036d54|title=UO, OSU, PSU, UP to cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus outbreak|publisher=KGW|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/pilots/2020/03/university-of-portland-pilots-cancel-all-future-spring-sports-events-activities-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=University of Portland Pilots cancel all future spring sports events, activities due to coronavirus|last=Brown|first=Tim|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> [[Lewis and Clark College]], [[Linfield College]], and [[Willamette University]] also implemented distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/university-of-portland-willamette-cancel-in-person-classes-latest-colleges-to-shift-amid-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=University of Portland, Willamette, Lewis & Clark, Linfield cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus concerns|last=Davis|first=Rob|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on public transportation==\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 16.jpg|thumb|upright|COVID-19 sign on a [[TriMet]] bus stop in [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]]]]\n\nThe Portland Area's regional transit agency, [[TriMet]], reported a significant decrease in ridership on March 19, 2020; approximately 140,000 fewer people rode TriMet vehicles compared to the weekday average in February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/03/trimet-is-not-cutting-service-yet-but-everything-is-on-the-table-amid-coronavirus-fears.html |last=Theen |first=Andrew |title=TriMet is not cutting service yet, but 'everything is on the table' amid coronavirus fears |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-sees-decrease-in-ridership-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |last1=Powell |first1=Meerah |last2=Vance |first2=Bryan M. |title=TriMet Sees Decrease In Ridership Amid Coronavirus Outbreak |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 28, the agency announced significant reductions to its services after recording a 47{{nbsp}}percent decrease in ridership.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://katu.com/news/local/trimet-to-adjust-schedules-because-of-steep-drop-in-ridership |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TriMet to adjust schedules because of steep drop in ridership |publisher=[[KATU]] |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Effective April 5, [[MAX Light Rail]] trains will run every 15{{nbsp}}minutes while [[WES Commuter Rail]] trains will run every 45{{nbsp}}minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-reduces-train-and-bus-service/ |last=Powell |first=Meerah |title=TriMet Reduces Train, Bus Service In Response To Decreased Ridership |publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> 84 bus lines will see schedule changes while the 272\u2013PDX Night Bus route will be suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |title=Reduced Service |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329202724/https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |archive-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Earlier on March 5, TriMet workers began disinfecting the interior surfaces of buses, MAX and WES trains, and LIFT [[paratransit]] vehicles nightly.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/05/amid-coronavirus-fear-trimet-begins-nightly-wipedown-of-bus-and-train-doors/ |last=Mesh |first=Aaron |title=Amid Coronavirus Fear, TriMet Begins Nightly Wipedown of Bus and Train Doors |publisher=[[Willamette Week]] |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Prevent>{{cite news |url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-pdx-trimet-and-others-are-doing-to-keep-customers-staff-safe-from-coronavirus/283-c1d5be93-c504-41f4-91a1-5468534eba33 |last=Cowley |first=Jared |title=What PDX, TriMet and others are doing to prevent the spread of coronavirus |publisher=[[KGW]] |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On its website,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/health/ |title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=[[TriMet]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325062205/https://trimet.org/health/ |archive-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> TriMet has requested the public to \"maintain six feet of distance from other riders and the operator.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/19/28168598/fewer-riders-more-cleaning-heightened-uncertainty-how-are-trimet-employees-managing-the-covid-19-outbreak |last=Stenvick |first=Blair |title=Fewer Riders, More Cleaning, Heightened Uncertainty: How Are TriMet Employees Managing the COVID-19 Outbreak? |publisher=[[Portland Mercury]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The agency has also asked people to \"only take transit if necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/23/trimet-please-only-take-transit-if-necessary.html |last=Danko |first=Pete |title=TriMet: 'Please only take transit if necessary' |publisher=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOther transit agencies across the region have adopted similar measures, as well as measures to assist community members in need. On March 19, [[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] (SMART) buses in [[Wilsonville, Oregon|Wilsonville]] began temporarily operating fare-free in support of transit-dependent commuters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/temporary-free-rides-all-smart-routes |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Temporary FREE RIDES on all SMART Routes |publisher=[[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|3|24|df=us}}, SMART services continue to operate without any schedule reductions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/transit-covid-19-coronavirus-updates |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TRANSIT COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=South Metro Area Regional Transit |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 23, the [[Portland Streetcar]] reduced its regular weekday schedule from every 15{{nbsp}}minutes to every 20{{nbsp}}minutes in response to the statewide stay-at-home order.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/news/2020/03/streetcar-service-will-reduce-to-20-minute-headways-beginning-march-24 |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Streetcar Service Will Reduce to 20-Minute Headways Beginning March 24 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 2, the [[Port of Portland (Oregon)|Port of Portland]] had increased the rate of cleanings at the [[Portland International Airport]] and at marine centers. The [[port authority]] focus on information and pay stations, shuttle buses, and valet booths, following recommendations issued by the county and CDC, and made hand sanitizer available for people using ground transportation.<ref name=Prevent/> The [[taxicab]] company Radio Cab also improved cleaning procedures.<ref name=Prevent/>\n\n==Impact on religion==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n[[File:Aletheia Bible Fellowship Web Sermons Only during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Sign of a Portland church live streaming sermons]]\n\nSeveral Portland area churches, mosques, synagogues, and other places of worship canceled or elected to live stream services, including [[Congregation Neveh Shalom]] and the [[First Unitarian Church of Portland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/religious-and-faith-communities-continue-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Religious And Faith Communities Continue Services Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Meerah|last=Powell|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/if-you-are-worshipping-this-weekend-you-might-want-to-check-ahead.html|title=Coronavirus and church: If you are worshipping this weekend, you might want to check ahead|date=March 14, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Portland's Bridgetown Church began offering services online via [[Zoom Video Communications]]. The city's largest mosque, [[Masjid As-Saber]], suspended [[Friday prayer]]s and asked worshippers to stay at home.<ref name=Open/>\n\nArchbishop [[Alexander King Sample]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland]] encouraged priests to \"be creative\" with regard to accessibility,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/world/churches-mosques-temples-coronavirus-spread/index.html|title=What churches, mosques and temples are doing to fight the spread of coronavirus|first=Daniel|last=Burke|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and \"issued directives for parishes to cancel any event over 250 people and encouraged those aged over 60 or with underlying medical issues to consider not attending Mass and dispensed them of the obligation\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.statesmanjournal.com/story/news/2020/03/13/oregon-coronavirus-school-closures-salem-keizer-public-schools/5040931002/|title=Coronavirus: Oregon schools close, doctors demand state action, warming shelter closed|first1=Whitney|last1=Woodworth|first2=Virginia|last2=Barreda|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=[[Statesman Journal]]|location=Salem, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Masses were canceled until April 14, which included Holy Week and Easter. Archbishop Sample said the announcement was \"by far one of the most difficult communications [he has] ever written\".<ref>{{cite news |title=PUBLIC MASSES HALTED TO SLOW VIRUS |url=https://catholicsentinel.org/Content/News/Local/Article/PUBLIC-MASSES-HALTED-TO-SLOW-VIRUS/2/35/39515 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Catholic Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> [[The Grotto]] has suspended Mass until March 31, but visitors are welcome to visit the outdoor sanctuary and Upper Gardens.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n==Crime==\nOn March 23, the [[Multnomah County Sheriff's Office]]'s said the crime rate for the month to date was lower than the rate for March 2019. The agency also reported lower jail bookings and moved some inmates at the Inverness Jail in northeast Portland into temporary dormitory-style housing to follow social distancing measures.<ref name=\"Crime\">{{cite news |last1=Heye |first1=Bob |title=Coronavirus and Crime: Jail releases, a rash of break-ins and one encouraging trend |url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-and-crime-jail-releases-a-rash-of-break-ins-and-one-encouraging-trend |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KATU |agency=Sinclair Broadcast Group |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[KATU]] reported on a string of business break-ins in the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=Crime/> The crisis group Call to Safety, which supports people experiencing [[domestic violence]], began receiving twice as many calls and more requests for shelter and other resources once stay-at-home orders were enforced.<ref name=\"domeshelter\">{{cite news |last1=Crombie |first1=Noelle |title=Calls to Oregon's domestic violence crisis lines spike amid coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/crime/2020/03/calls-to-oregons-domestic-violence-crisis-lines-spike-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |publisher=Advance Local Media |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Thousands of [[respirator]] masks valued at approximately $2,500 were stolen from the Rebuilding Center in north Portland in March. Some of the masks were recovered and donated to local hospitals.<ref name=Crime/><ref name=\"stealmask\">{{cite news |author1=Nexstar Media Wire |title=Thousands of stolen N95 masks recovered in Portland, donated |url=https://www.ksn.com/news/thousands-of-stolen-n95-masks-recovered-donated/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KSN |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other responses==\nOn March 27, Portland began nightly \"solidarity cheers\" to recognize health care and other frontline workers, similar to many other cities around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-urges-nightly-solidarity-cheer-for-frontline-coronavirus-workers.html|title=Portland urges nightly solidarity cheer for frontline coronavirus workers|first=Everton |last=Bailey Jr |date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.travelportland.com/about-us/covid-19/|title=COVID-19 and the Portland Community|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=Travel Portland}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Zielinski |first1=Alex |title=\"I hope everything I'm telling you isn't true\": A Portland Oncology Nurse On COVID-19 |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/21/28177144/i-hope-everything-im-telling-you-isnt-true-a-portland-oncology-nurse-on-covid-19 |work=Portland Mercury |date=March 21, 2020}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Oregon|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:2020 in Portland, Oregon|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Oregon]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health in Oregon]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon\n| width =\n| image         = File:Coronavirus responses in Portland Oregon.jpeg\n| image_size    = \n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Sign on a storefront in [[Portland, Oregon]], noting a temporary closure due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing coronavirus pandemic]]\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)\n| virus_strain = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome<br />coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2)\n| location = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| first_case =\n| arrival_date = <!-- or | dates = -->\n| date = \n| origin =\n| type =\n| confirmed_cases =\n| active_cases =\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths =\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|https://beta.portland.gov/novel-coronavirus-covid-19}}\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Portland, Oregon''', is an ongoing viral pandemic of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). Efforts to prevent the virus spreading include event postponements and cancellations, and facility closures.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus disease 2019|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2}}\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oregon}}\n[[File:Ghost Hug chalk writing on Hawthorne during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Chalk writing on a sidewalk in southeast Portland during the pandemic]]\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] is an ongoing [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The outbreak started in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]] province, [[China]], in December 2019. The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declared the outbreak to be a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] on 30 January 2020 and a pandemic on 11 March 2020.\n\nAs of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|conround|editlink=|ref=no}} cases of COVID-19 have been reported in more than 200 countries and territories, resulting in more than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|dround|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}} More than {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|recround|editlink=|ref=no}} people have recovered.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ref=yes}}\n\nThe pandemic was first confirmed to have spread to the United States in January 2020. Cases have been confirmed in all fifty U.S. states, [[Washington, D.C.]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=\"mariana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=samoanews.com|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|03|31|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases in the world and ranks third in the number of total deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The pandemic was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of Oregon on February 28, 2020.\n\n==Cases==\nOregon's first presumptive case was announced in Portland on February 28, 2020. Governor [[Kate Brown]] spoke and the director of the [[Oregon Health Authority]] confirmed someone from [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] who worked at Forest Hills Elementary School in [[Lake Oswego, Oregon|Lake Oswego]] was being treated at [[Hillsboro, Oregon|Hillsboro]]'s [[Kaiser Westside Medical Center]]. The [[Lake Oswego School District]] closed the school for cleaning.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |title=State officials announce first presumptive case of coronavirus in Oregon |url=https://www.kptv.com/news/state-officials-announce-first-presumptive-case-of-coronavirus-in-oregon/article_6ac26688-5a93-11ea-a0af-d346d4e06ef0.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[KPTV]] |date=February 28, 2020 |location=Portland, Oregon}}</ref><ref name=\"firstabc\">{{cite news |last1=Selsky |first1=Andrew |title=Oregon has 1st coronavirus case: elementary school employee |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/oregon-1st-coronavirus-case-elementary-school-employee-69298619 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |via=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> The first case in [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] and fifteenth in Oregon was confirmed on March 10; the patient was treatment at the [[Veterans Affairs Medical Center (Oregon)|Veterans Affairs Medical Center]].<ref name=\"case15\">{{cite news |title=Oregon confirms 15th coronavirus case in state |url=https://www.registerguard.com/news/20200310/oregon-confirms-15th-coronavirus-case-in-state |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[The Register-Guard]] |date=March 10, 2020 |location=Eugene, Oregon}}</ref> An employee who worked at the [[Wells Fargo Center (Portland, Oregon)|Wells Fargo Center]] tested positive on March 14, prompting building tenant [[Davis Wright Tremaine]] to close offices in Portland.<ref name=\"skyscraper\">{{cite news |last1=Rogoway |first1=Mike |title=Coronavirus case linked to downtown Portland skyscraper |url=https://pamplinmedia.com/pt/9-news/456350-372216-coronavirus-case-linked-to-downtown-portland-skyscraper-pwoff |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> More than 30 people in the Portland metropolitan area tested positive by April 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/strong-evidence-seen-that-oregons-coronavirus-restrictions-are-working.html |title=\u2018Strong evidence\u2019 seen that Oregon\u2019s coronavirus restrictions are working |webs=The Oregonian |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n{{Main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Multnomah County Library Northwest branch with closure notice during 2020 coronavirus epidemic.jpg|thumb|left|Closure notice posted at the [[Northwest Library]] on March 16, 2020]]\n\nOn March 13, the [[Portland Police Bureau]] announced a reduction of in-person responses to reduce virus transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kobi5.com/news/portland-police-reduce-in-person-responses-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-123900/|title=Portland police reduce in-person responses amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|website=KOBI-TV NBC5 / KOTI-TV NBC2|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/487984-police-nationwide-ask-criminals-to-halt-activity|title=Police nationwide ask criminals to halt activity during coronavirus outbreak|first=Justine|last=Coleman|date=March 17, 2020|website=TheHill}}</ref> [[Multnomah County Library]] closed all branch libraries and [[Portland Parks and Recreation]] (PPR) closed arts and community centers, sports facilities, and swimming pools, based on recommendations issued by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], [[Multnomah County Health Department]], and the Oregon Health Authority. PPR canceled athletic programs and indoor activities at community centers, but did not close golf courses, natural areas, parks, playgrounds, or trails, or cancel outdoor events for less than 250 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/covid--closures-multnomah-county-libraries-some-portland-parks-rec/article_d56dbd54-659a-11ea-a9dc-637432f6280c.html|title=COVID-19 closures: Multnomah County libraries, some Portland Parks & Rec facilities shut down|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Multnomah County Chair Deborah Kafoury announced plans to add as many as 400 beds for county residents affected by the pandemic requiring shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/multnomah-county-to-add-hundreds-of-homeless-shelter-beds-within-the-week-for-people-with-symptoms-of-coronavirus.html|title=Multnomah County to add hundreds of homeless shelter beds within the week to help with coronavirus|first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 17, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> 120 beds were made available at the PPR-owned [[Charles Jordan Community Center]] in north Portland on March 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/first-coronavirus-related-emergency-homeless-shelter-to-open-in-north-portland.html|title=First coronavirus-related emergency homeless shelter to open in North Portland|first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 19, 2020| work=The Oregonian}}</ref> [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]]'s [[Oregon Convention Center]], unable to host events since March 12, was converted into a temporary shelter with 130\u2013140 beds. The Joint Office of Homeless Services, a collaboration between Metro and Multnomah County, hoped to open additional beds for healthy individuals as overflow from existing shelters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/oregon-convention-center-shelter/283-3f46becb-f2fa-4865-9cc1-65b35c741085|title=Oregon Convention Center to become temporary coronavirus-related homeless shelter|publisher=[[KGW]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/homeless-will-find-refuge-at-oregon-convention-center/|title=Homeless will find refuge at Oregon Convention Center|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=[[KOIN (TV)|KOIN]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Trucks normally used by Multnomah Country Library and for animal control were repurposed to assist with the convention center conversion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/tape-and-two-hours-to-transform-oregon-convention-center-into-coronavirus-homeless-shelter.html|title=Tape and 2 hours to transform Oregon Convention Center into coronavirus homeless shelter|first=Molly |last=Harbarger |date=March 21, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 22, Mayor [[Ted Wheeler]] said he was prepared to issue a [[stay-at-home order]] for Portland residents if Governor Brown would not issue a similar order for Oregon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/wheeler-to-brown-issue-statewide-stay-at-home-order/|title=Wheeler to Brown: Issue statewide stay-at-home order|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/mayor-wheeler-on-stay-at-home-order-im-ready-to-act-for-portland-tomorrow|title=Mayor Wheeler on stay-at-home order: 'I'm ready to act for Portland tomorrow'|date=March 22, 2020|publisher=[[KATU]]|location=Portland, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The governor was also pressured by 25 Portland-area mayors, Metro's council, multiple county chairs, and other elected and health officials. She issued an executive order on March 23 requiring home [[Isolation (health care)|isolation]] for Oregonians, with some exceptions, and to practice [[social distancing]]. Violators may be punished with 30 days in jail and fines as high as $1,250 as a class C [[misdemeanor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-stay-at-home-order-coronavirus-covid-19-kate-brown/|title=Gov. Kate Brown Issues Order Directing Oregonians To 'Stay Home'|first=Dirk|last=VanderHart|date=March 2, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The Portland Police Bureau confirmed criminal citations were a \"last resort measure\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/23/portland-police-can-now-issue-criminal-citations-to-those-who-violate-browns-stay-at-home-order/|title=Portland Police May Now Issue Criminal Citations to Anyone Who Violates Brown\u2019s Stay at Home Order|date=March 23, 2020 |first1=Tess |last1=Riski |newspaper=Willamette Week}}</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n{{Main|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Hand sanitizer and gloves sold out due to Coronavirus 10 57 26 366000.jpeg|thumb|right|Empty [[latex glove]] shelves at a [[Rite Aid]] store in [[downtown Portland]]]]\n\n[[Delta Air Lines]] reduced flights between Portland and Japan. United Airlines cut 4 of 20 flights from Portland as well as one from Eugene. [[Sun Country Airlines]] reduced flights between Portland and Honolulu, Las Vegas, and San Francisco.<ref name=Outlook>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-darkens-oregons-economic-outlook-but-impacts-are-muted-for-now.html |title=Coronavirus darkens Oregon's economic outlook, but impacts are muted -- for now |first=Mike |last= Rogoway |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchool closures and event cancellations prompted people to stock up on groceries. Long lines were seen at grocery stores and food pantries throughout the Portland metropolitan area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-grocery-stores-and-food-pantries-busy-as-covid-/article_67560a58-6656-11ea-b7d7-c3c87e0e2492.html|title=Portland grocery stores and food pantries busy as COVID-19 closures begin|first=John|last=Hendricks|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Local [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] dispensaries saw an increased demand as customers stocked up in case stores were forced to close temporarily.<ref name=Open>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/oregon-portland-coronavirus-covid-19-whats-open/|title=Life In The Time Of Coronavirus: What's Still Open In Oregon?|first=Donald|last=Orr|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[Oregon Liquor Control Commission]] (OLCC) permitted stores to operate via curbside pick-up and home delivery temporarily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/weve-been-having-420-every-day-for-the-last-2-weeks-oregon-pot-shops-see-spike-in-business-with-new-curbside-delivery/283-163e563c-a5e4-4b2a-87e1-76578a607346|title=\u2018We\u2019ve been having 4/20 every day\u2019: Oregon pot shops see spike in business with new curbside delivery|website=KGW}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/at-home-because-of-the-coronavirus-shutdown-heres-who-delivers-cannabis-products-in-portland.html|title=At home because of the coronavirus shutdown? Here's who delivers cannabis products in Portland|first=Lizzy|last=Acker|date=March 25, 2020|website=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186115/oregon-cannabis-dispensaries-now-allowed-to-offer-curbside-pickup|title=Oregon Cannabis Dispensaries Now Allowed to Offer Curbside Pickup|first1=Wm Steven|last1=Humphrey|date=March 23, 2020|work=Portland Mercury}}</ref>\n\n===Business closures and event cancellations===\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 15.jpg|thumb|left|upright|People practicing social distancing while waiting to enter [[New Seasons Market]] in the [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]] neighborhood]]\n\n[[Adidas]] closed offices at Montgomery Park and Portland Village after two employees had close content with someone who tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/nba/adidas-closes-north-american-headquarters-amid-covid-19-pandemic|title=Adidas closes North American headquarters amid COVID-19 pandemic|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Powell's Books]] five stores closed,<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/powells-books-closes-as-coronavirus-spreads-in-portland-metro|title=Powell's Books closes as coronavirus spreads in Portland metro|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and laid off most staff members.<ref name=Open/> [[Portland Incubator Experiment]] canceled PIE Demo Day; the March 19 event scheduled to be held at [[Revolution Hall]] was held online.<ref name=Stein/> On March 25, [[Daimler Trucks North America]] shut down a plant on Swan Island until April 6.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/daimler-trucks-shutting-down-portland-plant-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Daimler Trucks shutting down Portland plant amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike |last=Rogoway |date=March 25, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref> Portland-based companies [[Puppet (company)|Puppet]] and [[Vacasa]] laid off employees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2020/03/portland-marketing-technology-startup-opal-lays-off-20-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Portland technology companies lay off dozens amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Mike|last=Rogoway|date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n\n[[Oaks Amusement Park]] and the [[Oaks Park Roller Skating Rink]], the [[Oregon Historical Society]], the [[Oregon Zoo]], [[Portland Children's Museum]],<ref name=Stein>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/event-cancellationspostponements-due-to-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=Events canceled in Oregon over the next months|first=Rosemarie |last=Stein |date=March 10, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref> and [[Portland Japanese Garden]] closed as well.<ref name=Rogoway/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/list-portland-area-museums-attractions-closed-amid-coronavirus-response/|title=LIST: Portland area museums, attractions closed amid coronavirus response|date=March 15, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> As of March 19, the [[Portland Art Museum]] and [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] are closed through March 31 and mid April, respectively.<ref name=Open/> The [[Crystal Ballroom (Portland, Oregon)|Crystal Ballroom]] and [[Hawthorne Theatre]] canceled or postponed planned shows through mid April.<ref name=Open/> The [[City Club of Portland]] canceled activities.<ref name=MCL>{{Cite news|last=Monahan|first=Rachel|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/city/2020/03/13/multnomah-county-library-closed-as-of-today-in-response-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Multnomah County Library Closed in Response to the Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 13, 2020|work=[[Willamette Week]]|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The [[Portland Rose Festival]] has postponed annual events, including the [[Starlight Parade]], indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/2020/03/19/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed-indefinitely/|title=The Portland Rose Festival Has Been Postponed Indefinitely|date=March 19, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/entertainment/2020/03/the-portland-rose-festival-has-been-postponed.html|title=The 2020 Portland Rose Festival has been postponed due to coronavirus crisis|first1=Rosemarie |last1=Stein |first2=Kjerstin |last2=Gabrielson |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Herbal Products Association]]'s Hemp-CBD Congress, scheduled for mid April at the [[Benson Hotel]], was canceled.<ref name=Stein/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/09/28113766/coronavirus-and-cannabis-how-pot-is-impacted-by-a-pandemic |title=Coronavirus and Cannabis: How Pot Is Impacted by a Pandemic |first1=Josh |last1=Jardine  |date=March 9, 2020 |newspaper=[[Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[Road Runners Club of America]]'s annual convention, slated to be held at the [[Hilton Portland Hotel]] during March 19\u201322, was also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> A conference on [[affordable housing]], climate, and community stability featuring [[Julian Castro]] during April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[TechfestNW]] was to be held at [[Portland State University]] during April 2\u20133, but was rescheduled for August 6\u20137. April 11's Cider Rite of Spring was rescheduled for November, and Design Week Festival was moved from the week starting April 18 to August 1\u20138. The arts and technology festival [[XOXO (festival)|XOXO]] scheduled for September has been canceled.<ref name=Stein/> [[Pride Northwest]]'s annual [[pride parade]] has been postponed, and the Portland Retro Gaming Expo has been canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/23/28186244/todays-coronavirus-news-roundup-brown-issues-stay-home-order-dems-slam-gop-stimulus-bill-and-trump-keeps-getting-in-the-way|title=Today's Coronavirus News Roundup: Brown Issues \"Stay Home\" Order, Dems Slam GOP Stimulus Bill, and Trump Keeps Getting in the Way|date=March 23, 2020|work=[ Portland Mercury}}</ref> The [[Waterfront Blues Festival]], slated for July 2\u20135, was canceled on March 25.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/waterfront-blues-festival-canceled-for-2020-will-return-in-2021.html|title=Waterfront Blues Festival canceled for 2020, will return in 2021|first=Samantha|last=Swindler|date=March 24, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/music/2020/03/24/the-waterfront-blues-festival-has-been-canceled-due-to-the-pandemic/|title=The Waterfront Blues Festival Has Been Canceled Due to the Pandemic|date=March 24, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/organizers-cancel-waterfront-blues-festival-over-coronavirus-concerns|title=Organizers cancel Waterfront Blues Festival over coronavirus concerns|author=KATU Staff|date=March 24, 2020|website=KATU}}</ref>\n\nWhile cheer and dance competitions were still being held at the Oregon Convention Center in early March,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/crowds-gather-at-convention-center-despite-virus-concerns/|title=Crowds gather at convention center despite virus concerns|date=March 7, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> many events planned to be hosted at the venue were canceled. On February 5, the Materials Show scheduled for February 12\u201313 was canceled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-trade-show-canceled-over-coronavirus-concerns/article_28d3fde8-4889-11ea-bcd6-8bb625985644.html|title=Portland trade show canceled over coronavirus concerns|date=February 5, 2020|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://q13fox.com/2020/02/05/portland-convention-rescheduled-over-coronavirus-fears/|title=Portland convention rescheduled over coronavirus fears|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Gem Faire and the Multnomah County Democrats' annual Celsi Celebration slated for the weekend of March 21 were also canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 6, organizers of the Go West Summit, an international travel conference for March 24\u201327 expecting approximately 800 people, was postponed.<ref name=Hotels>{{Cite news|last=Iboshi|first=Kyle|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/portland-hotels-see-significant-room-cancellations-travel-conference-postponed/283-6d3b08c3-7a8a-4b56-a65c-bac4919cd73d|title=Portland hotels see 'significant' room cancellations; travel conference postponed|date=March 6, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The Oregon Dental Association's annual Oregon Dental Conference for April 2\u20134 was canceled.<ref name=Stein/> On March 9, the Burning Cat event being organized by the [[Exploding Kittens (company)|company]] behind the card game [[Exploding Kittens]] for May was canceled.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/09/event-canceled-at-oregon-convention-center-amid.html|title=Event canceled at Oregon Convention Center|last=|first=|date=March 9, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, restrictions prompted the closures of amusement parks, barber shops, bowling alleys, gyms, hair and nail salons, malls, spas, and theaters.<ref name=Lillard>{{Cite web|last=Nemec|first=Andrew|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/blazers/2020/03/damian-lillard-joins-nba-instagram-encourages-social-distancing-staying-home-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Damian Lillard joins NBA Instagram, encourages social distancing, staying home amid coronavirus outbreak|date=March 23, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n\n====Film industry and the performing arts====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n{{multiple image\n | width = 200\n | image1 = Bagdad Theater, Portland Oregon, during coronavirus closure.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | image2 = Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus .jpeg\n | alt2 = \n | footer = [[Bagdad Theatre]] (left) and [[Laurelhurst Theater]] (right) with marquee messages acknowledging closures because of the pandemic  \n}}\n\nLocal movie theaters were forced to close temporarily. Among them were [[Cinema 21]] and [[Laurelhurst Theater]],<ref name=Venues/> which was unable to continue operating with capacity limits and social distancing measures, despite efforts.<ref name=Open/> On March 13, the [[Hollywood Theatre (Portland, Oregon)|Hollywood Theatre]] confirmed plans to close from March 14 to April 8; previously, the theater was limiting capacity to 250 people per Oregon's ban on events and other social gatherings.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gormley|first=Shannon|url=https://www.wweek.com/arts/movies/2020/03/13/portlands-hollywood-theatre-will-close-until-april-8/|title=Portland's Hollywood Theatre Will Close Until April 8|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Movie Madness Video]], a [[video rental shop]] and [[history of film]] museum, closed and waived late fees on rentals.<ref name=Open/> Cinema 21 later allowed people to stream independent films at home.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cook|first=Katherine|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/entertainment/local-theaters-let-customers-stream-independent-films-from-home/283-d3c31d70-3985-4ed4-8047-284195efcc54|title=Local theaters let customers stream independent films from home|date=March 30, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=Apr 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall]] and Brunish Theatre at [[Antoinette Hatfield Hall]] closed,<ref name=Venues>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-response-public-venues-omsi-childrens-museum-ohs-close-for-2-weeks.html|title=Oregon closures: Libraries, recreation centers, museums, ski resorts, zoo, retailers|first=Rosemarie |last=Stein |date=March 13, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref> forcing the [[Oregon Symphony]] to cancel performances.<ref name=Rogoway/> Initially, the symphony canceled performances between March 13 and April 6.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/12/oregon-symphony-cancels-march-early-april-shows.html|title=Oregon Symphony cancels March, Early April shows|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Portland Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> 76 musicians, two conductors, and 19 staff members were laid off, and the organization's [[President (corporate title)|president]] and [[chief executive officer]] has submitted an appeal for funding to Governor Brown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-symphony-lays-off-orchestra-conductors-and-staff-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html|title=Oregon Symphony lays off orchestra, conductors and staff amid coronavirus crisis|first=Nathan |last=Rizzo |date=March 20, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Portland Center Stage]] canceled productions for eight weeks (through April 8) and furloughed 78 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/radio/article/coronavirus-fears-affect-oregons-biggest-arts-organizations/|title=Coronavirus Closures Endanger Oregon's Most Prominent Arts Organizations|first1=Steven|last1=Tonthat|first2=Eric|last2=Slade|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Portland Opera]] canceled March 20\u201328 performances of ''[[Bajazet (opera)|Bajazet]]'' at Antoinette Hatfield Hall's Newmark Theatre.<ref name=Stein/> The arts center [[Disjecta]] canceled or postponed activities.<ref name=Stein/> The [[Northwest Film Center]] closed and the Portland International Film Festival was canceled.<ref name=Open/> [[The Old Church (Portland, Oregon)|The Old Church]] has postponed concerts through April 8, forcing [[Chamber Music Northwest]] to reschedule some performances.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n====Food service and restaurant industry====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n[[File:Businesses closed in Portland because of Coronavirus16 13 59 290000.jpeg|thumb|left|Sign noting [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]]'s closure]]\n\nThe city's restaurant industry was \"completely obliterated\" by the state's bar and restaurant ban.<ref name=Rogoway>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/business/2020/03/coronavirus-brings-oregon-a-sudden-economic-catastrophe-the-worst-week-ever.html|title=Coronavirus brings Oregon a sudden economic catastrophe: 'The worst week ever'|first=Mike |last=Rogoway |date=March 22, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref> Governor Brown banned in-house consumption across Oregon, effective March 17. Some restaurants closed entirely, while others implemented [[food delivery]] and [[take-out]] operations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/responding-to-coronavirus-pandemic-vegan-fine-dining-restaurant-farm-spirit-upscale-steakhouse-el-gaucho-will-close-temporarily.html |title=Portland restaurants close dining rooms; some offer delivery|first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 13, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Closures>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/13/21178995/covid-19-coronavirus-closures-portland|title=A Number of Restaurants Once Open for Takeout and Delivery Have Closed List Last Week|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 13, 2020|website=[[Eater (website)|Eater Portland]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> [[Acadia: A New Orleans Bistro]], [[Doug Fir Lounge]], [[Ken's Artisan Pizza]], [[Le Bistro Montage]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/dining/2020/03/portland-restaurants-closed-due-to-coronavirus.html |title=Here are all the Portland restaurants to close or embrace takeout, delivery-only service |first=Michael |last=Russell |date=March 14, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[Le Pigeon]], [[Nostrana (restaurant)|Nostrana]], [[Olympia Provisions]], [[Pok Pok]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/25/21194167/pok-pok-closed|title=The Pok Pok Empire Closes Indefinitely in Wake of Coronavirus Crisis|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 25, 2020|website=Eater Portland}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/how-to-make-pok-poks-fish-sauce-wings-at-home.html|title=With Pok Pok restaurants closed, here's how to make those famous fish sauce wings at home|first=Michael|last=Russell|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref> and [[Screen Door (restaurant)|Screen Door]] all closed.<ref name=Closures/> [[Hot Lips Pizza]], [[Oven and Shaker]], and [[Sizzle Pie]] continued pizza pickup and delivery service, as of March 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/27/21194686/where-to-find-a-pizza-during-the-restaurant-shutdown|title=Where to Find a Pizza During the Restaurant Shutdown|first=Sam|last=Hill|date=March 27, 2020|website=Eater Portland}}</ref> [[Shine Distillery and Grill]] began producing [[hand sanitizer]] from alcohol for customers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/us/2020/03/19/oregon-shine-distillery-making-hand-sanitizer-coronavirus-bts-ctn-vpx.cnn|title=Oregon distillery is making its own in-house hand sanitizer and giving it away|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Andi|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/10/a-portland-distillery-is-making-its-own-hand-cleaner-in-the-wake-of-coronavirus/|title=A Portland Distillery Is Making Its Own Hand Cleaner in the Wake of Coronavirus|date=March 10, 2020|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-distillery-makes-hand-sanitizer-to-give-to-customers/article_c79023bc-6292-11ea-832b-e3a4b8d06435.html|title=Portland distillery makes hand sanitizer to give to customers|first=Audrey|last=Weil|publisher=KPTV}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/11/21174997/shine-distillery-hand-cleaning-solution|title=North Portland's Shine Distillery Is Giving Away House-Made, 80-Percent-Alcohol Hand 'Cleaner'|first=Brooke|last=Jackson-Glidden|date=March 11, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The website 'PDX2Go' was created to track businesses still accepting orders, and some food carts continued to operate.<ref name=Open/>\n\nTwelve of 27 laid off [[Crush Bar]] employees staged a protest and accused the owner of \"[breaking] the law by denying their use of accrued sick hours to cover lost wages\". The demonstration was supposed to last for 24 hours but was stopped by police after an hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdx.eater.com/2020/3/17/21184325/crush-bar-sit-in-layoffs-covid-19|title=Crush Bar Employees Staged Sit-In After Mass Layoffs [Updated]|first=Alex|last=Frane|date=March 17, 2020|website=Eater Portland|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[strip club]] Lucky Devil Lounge continued to offer a full menu with home delivery service by \"scantily clad strippers\" under the business operation Boober Eats.<ref name=Lucky>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-strip-club-forced-to-close-so-dancers-now-do-delivery.html|title=Portland strip club forced to close, so dancers now do delivery|first=Samantha |last=Swindler |date=March 22, 2020 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wweek.com/bars/2020/03/17/a-portland-strip-club-has-started-a-meal-delivery-service-where-dancers-bring-food-directly-to-your-door-to-your-home/|title=A Portland Strip Club Has Started a Meal Delivery Service Where Dancers Bring Food Directly to Your Door|work=Willamette Week|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/strippers-staff-boober-eats-delivery-service-during-coronavirus-lockdown/|title=Strippers staff 'Boober Eats' delivery service during coronavirus lockdown|first=Hannah|last=Sparks|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Approximately 25 strippers have participated; dancers are driven and protected by security guards, armed with gloves, masks, and hand sanitizer,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/boober-eats-lucky-devil-lounge-strip-club-covid-19-coronavirus-quarantine-971544/|title=With Clubs Closed for COVID-19, Strippers in Portland, Oregon, Take to Topless Food Delivery|first1=E. J.|last1=Dickson|first2=E. J.|last2=Dickson|date=March 23, 2020|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and touching by customers is not allowed.<ref name=Lucky/>\n\n====Hospitality industry====\nThe [[hospitality industry]] also experienced a wave of guest cancellations followed by a decline in bookings.<ref name=Hotels/> The [[Jupiter Hotel (Portland, Oregon)|Jupiter Hotel]] laid off half its staff by March 18 after daily occupancy rates fell to 7\u201320 percent.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/oregon-hotels-lay-off-workers-question-survival-after-wave-of-coronavirus-cancellations.html |title=Oregon hotels lay off workers, question futures after wave of coronavirus cancellations |first=Jamie |last=Goldberg |date=March 19, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Jupiter partnered with Multnomah County to use the hotel's 81 rooms as a temporary homeless shelter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pamplinmedia.com/go/42-news/459054-373887-portlands-jupiter-hotel-becomes-coronavirus-shelter-for-medically-fragile-homeless-people|title=Portland's Jupiter Hotel becomes coronavirus shelter for medically fragile homeless people|first=Molly|last=Harbarger|date=March 26, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katu.com/news/local/portland-hotel-donates-rooms-to-help-homeless-with-coronavirus-symptoms-stay-in-quarantine|title=Portland hotel donates rooms to help homeless with coronavirus symptoms stay in quarantine|first=KATU|last=Staff|date=March 26, 2020|website=KATU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hanson|first=Nate |url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/homeless/jupiter-hotel-homeless-shelter-portland-coronavirus/283-370d4b13-f607-4460-98ed-6a6d5465d83d|title=Jupiter Hotel in Portland to become homeless shelter during coronavirus pandemic|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=KGW}}</ref> [[The Nines (hotel)|The Nines]] suspended hotel and restaurant operations on March 19, effective March 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kptv.com/news/portland-luxury-hotel-nines-suspends-services-due-to-covid/article_6b47548a-6a40-11ea-adb7-4f0a8a298283.html|title=Portland luxury hotel Nines suspends services due to COVID-19|publisher=KPTV|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Impact on professional sports====\n[[File:Providence Park box office notice - closed due to COVID-19 epidemic, 3-16-2020.jpg|thumb|Box office closure sign at [[Providence Park]], home of the [[Portland Timbers]] and [[Portland Thorns FC]], on March 16, 2020]]\n\nFollowing season suspensions by the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://katu.com/news/local/mls-suspends-season-due-to-coronavirus-delaying-timbers-season|title=MLS suspends season due to coronavirus, delaying Timbers season|first=Evan|last=Schreiber|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=KATU|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] and [[Portland Timbers]] canceled games.<ref name=Rogoway/> The Trail Blazers and Timbers games averaged approximately 19,000 and 25,000 people at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/service-industry-portland-coronavirus-nba-mls-moda-center/|title=Portland Service Industry Reeling And Uncertain With NBA, MLS On Hold|first1=Troy|last1=Brynelson|first2=Bradley W.|last2=Parks|date=March 16, 2020|publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> MLS initially announced a 30-day suspension, when the Timbers were scheduled to play at [[Providence Park]] five times between March 12 and mid April.<ref name=NBC>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/northwest/portland-timbers/breaking-mls-suspends-season-due-coronavirus|title=BREAKING: MLS suspends season due to coronavirus|date=March 12, 2020|website=NBC Sports Northwest|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The soccer league extended the suspension to eight weeks on March 19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/major-league-soccer-extends-season-postponement-for-another-month/283-d59a5f0d-0416-4929-893e-73399e61476f|title=Major League Soccer extends season postponement for another month|date=March 19, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The [[Portland Thorns FC]]'s pre-season tournament slated for March 29 \u2013 April 4 was canceled on March 12, shortly before the [[National Women's Soccer League]] canceled pre-season games across the league.<ref name=Thorns>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/portland-thorns/2020/03/portland-thorns-cancel-preseason-tournament-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Thorns cancel preseason tournament amid coronavirus outbreak|first=Jamie|last=Goldberg|date=March 12, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref> Timbers and Thorns tickets will be valid for rescheduled matches, as of March 12.<ref name=Thorns/> On March 17, the Timbers and Thorns announced part-time workers would still receive compensation for canceled games, among other community initiatives.<ref>{{Cite news|author=KGW Staff|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/portland-timbers-thorns-to-pay-part-time-workers/283-ae77774b-161a-4b19-9699-266bd9ef8e26|title=Portland Timbers, Thorns to pay part-time workers for games missed during coronavirus outbreak|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=KGW|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Damian Lillard]] encouraged fans to remain at home and practice social distancing. He said on the NBA's [[Instagram]] account on March 23, \"I've been washing my hands, social distancing \u2014 keep your space. Don't join in crowds, stay in small groups. It'd be best to stay in the house. I hope everybody is stocked up on everything they need so they can stay safe. Do everything the way we've been asked to help this pass faster. Like I said, ya'll stay safe, ya'll be good, man.\"<ref name=Lillard/>\n\n==Impact on education==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 05.jpg|thumb|Sign noting [[Reed College]]'s closure]]\n\nGovernor Brown initially closed schools all K\u201312 schools through March 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/portland-metro-school-district-tigard-tualatin-lake-oswego-coronavirus-board-meeting-emergency-covid-students/|title=Brown orders all K-12 schools closed through March|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=KOIN|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A four-week extension was added; students are scheduled to return on April 28. [[Portland Public Schools (Oregon)|Portland Public Schools]] designated 15 buildings as sites for student meal distributions, and has considered providing 45,000 devices to students for [[distance education]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-public-schools-begins-plans-for-6-week-closure.html|title=Portland Public Schools begins plans for 6-week closure|first=Eder|last=Campuzano|date=March 18, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> High school and college graduation ceremonies were canceled.<ref name=Rogoway/>\n\nAll Multnomah County Library branches were closed on March 13.<ref name=MCL/> The library system waived late fees and continued to provide public [[Wi-Fi]].<ref name=Open/>\n\nStudents at [[Oregon Health & Science University]] and the University of Portland began offering childcare and errand services for local health care professionals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-area-healthcare-workers-can-request-free-childcare-other-support-from-local-medical-and-nursing-students.html|title=Portland-area healthcare workers can request free childcare, other support from local medical and nursing students|first=Amy|last=Wang|date=March 21, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Universities and collegiate sports===\n[[Portland State University]] canceled in-person final exams,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wweek.com/news/schools/2020/03/12/portland-state-university-cancels-in-person-final-exams-moves-spring-classes-online/|title=Portland State University Cancels In-Person Final Exams, Moves Spring Classes Online|last=Mesh|first=Aaron|last2=|first2=|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=Willamette Week|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=|first3=}}</ref> and eliminated in-person classes for the spring term, opting for distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-state-university-will-not-resume-in-person-classes-this-spring.html|title=Portland State will not resume in-person classes this spring|last=Goldberg|first=Jamie|date=March 19, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[University of Portland]] moved to online instruction and canceled all sports games and practices for the spring term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/university-of-oregon-classes-remotely-coronavirus/283-b5b5abc3-463f-442a-abc6-964fb9036d54|title=UO, OSU, PSU, UP to cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus outbreak|publisher=KGW|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/pilots/2020/03/university-of-portland-pilots-cancel-all-future-spring-sports-events-activities-due-to-coronavirus.html|title=University of Portland Pilots cancel all future spring sports events, activities due to coronavirus|last=Brown|first=Tim|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> [[Lewis and Clark College]], [[Linfield College]], and [[Willamette University]] also implemented distance learning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/university-of-portland-willamette-cancel-in-person-classes-latest-colleges-to-shift-amid-coronavirus-concerns.html|title=University of Portland, Willamette, Lewis & Clark, Linfield cancel in-person classes amid coronavirus concerns|last=Davis|first=Rob|date=March 12, 2020|newspaper=The Oregonian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on public transportation==\n[[File:Portland, Oregon during the coronavirus pandemic, March 2020 - 16.jpg|thumb|upright|COVID-19 sign on a [[TriMet]] bus stop in [[Woodstock, Portland, Oregon|Woodstock]]]]\n\nThe Portland Area's regional transit agency, [[TriMet]], reported a significant decrease in ridership on March 19, 2020; approximately 140,000 fewer people rode TriMet vehicles compared to the weekday average in February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2020/03/trimet-is-not-cutting-service-yet-but-everything-is-on-the-table-amid-coronavirus-fears.html |last=Theen |first=Andrew |title=TriMet is not cutting service yet, but 'everything is on the table' amid coronavirus fears |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-sees-decrease-in-ridership-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |last1=Powell |first1=Meerah |last2=Vance |first2=Bryan M. |title=TriMet Sees Decrease In Ridership Amid Coronavirus Outbreak |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 28, the agency announced significant reductions to its services after recording a 47{{nbsp}}percent decrease in ridership.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://katu.com/news/local/trimet-to-adjust-schedules-because-of-steep-drop-in-ridership |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TriMet to adjust schedules because of steep drop in ridership |publisher=[[KATU]] |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Effective April 5, [[MAX Light Rail]] trains will run every 15{{nbsp}}minutes while [[WES Commuter Rail]] trains will run every 45{{nbsp}}minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/trimet-reduces-train-and-bus-service/ |last=Powell |first=Meerah |title=TriMet Reduces Train, Bus Service In Response To Decreased Ridership |publisher=Oregon Public Broadcasting |date=March 28, 2020 |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> 84 bus lines will see schedule changes while the 272\u2013PDX Night Bus route will be suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |title=Reduced Service |publisher=TriMet |access-date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329202724/https://trimet.org/alerts/reducedservice.htm |archive-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Earlier on March 5, TriMet workers began disinfecting the interior surfaces of buses, MAX and WES trains, and LIFT [[paratransit]] vehicles nightly.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wweek.com/news/2020/03/05/amid-coronavirus-fear-trimet-begins-nightly-wipedown-of-bus-and-train-doors/ |last=Mesh |first=Aaron |title=Amid Coronavirus Fear, TriMet Begins Nightly Wipedown of Bus and Train Doors |publisher=[[Willamette Week]] |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=Prevent>{{cite news |url=https://www.kgw.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/what-pdx-trimet-and-others-are-doing-to-keep-customers-staff-safe-from-coronavirus/283-c1d5be93-c504-41f4-91a1-5468534eba33 |last=Cowley |first=Jared |title=What PDX, TriMet and others are doing to prevent the spread of coronavirus |publisher=[[KGW]] |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On its website,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/health/ |title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=[[TriMet]] |access-date=March 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325062205/https://trimet.org/health/ |archive-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> TriMet has requested the public to \"maintain six feet of distance from other riders and the operator.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/19/28168598/fewer-riders-more-cleaning-heightened-uncertainty-how-are-trimet-employees-managing-the-covid-19-outbreak |last=Stenvick |first=Blair |title=Fewer Riders, More Cleaning, Heightened Uncertainty: How Are TriMet Employees Managing the COVID-19 Outbreak? |publisher=[[Portland Mercury]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The agency has also asked people to \"only take transit if necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2020/03/23/trimet-please-only-take-transit-if-necessary.html |last=Danko |first=Pete |title=TriMet: 'Please only take transit if necessary' |publisher=[[Portland Business Journal]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOther transit agencies across the region have adopted similar measures, as well as measures to assist community members in need. On March 19, [[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] (SMART) buses in [[Wilsonville, Oregon|Wilsonville]] began temporarily operating fare-free in support of transit-dependent commuters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/temporary-free-rides-all-smart-routes |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Temporary FREE RIDES on all SMART Routes |publisher=[[South Metro Area Regional Transit]] |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|3|24|df=us}}, SMART services continue to operate without any schedule reductions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ridesmart.com/transit/page/transit-covid-19-coronavirus-updates |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=TRANSIT COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updates |publisher=South Metro Area Regional Transit |date=March 18, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> On March 23, the [[Portland Streetcar]] reduced its regular weekday schedule from every 15{{nbsp}}minutes to every 20{{nbsp}}minutes in response to the statewide stay-at-home order.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/news/2020/03/streetcar-service-will-reduce-to-20-minute-headways-beginning-march-24 |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Streetcar Service Will Reduce to 20-Minute Headways Beginning March 24 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |date=March 23, 2020 |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 2, the [[Port of Portland (Oregon)|Port of Portland]] had increased the rate of cleanings at the [[Portland International Airport]] and at marine centers. The [[port authority]] focus on information and pay stations, shuttle buses, and valet booths, following recommendations issued by the county and CDC, and made hand sanitizer available for people using ground transportation.<ref name=Prevent/> The [[taxicab]] company Radio Cab also improved cleaning procedures.<ref name=Prevent/>\n\n==Impact on religion==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n[[File:Aletheia Bible Fellowship Web Sermons Only during Coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|Sign of a Portland church live streaming sermons]]\n\nSeveral Portland area churches, mosques, synagogues, and other places of worship canceled or elected to live stream services, including [[Congregation Neveh Shalom]] and the [[First Unitarian Church of Portland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/religious-and-faith-communities-continue-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Religious And Faith Communities Continue Services Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Meerah|last=Powell|date=March 26, 2020|publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/if-you-are-worshipping-this-weekend-you-might-want-to-check-ahead.html|title=Coronavirus and church: If you are worshipping this weekend, you might want to check ahead|date=March 14, 2020|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Portland's Bridgetown Church began offering services online via [[Zoom Video Communications]]. The city's largest mosque, [[Masjid As-Saber]], suspended [[Friday prayer]]s and asked worshippers to stay at home.<ref name=Open/>\n\nArchbishop [[Alexander King Sample]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland]] encouraged priests to \"be creative\" with regard to accessibility,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/world/churches-mosques-temples-coronavirus-spread/index.html|title=What churches, mosques and temples are doing to fight the spread of coronavirus|first=Daniel|last=Burke|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> and \"issued directives for parishes to cancel any event over 250 people and encouraged those aged over 60 or with underlying medical issues to consider not attending Mass and dispensed them of the obligation\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.statesmanjournal.com/story/news/2020/03/13/oregon-coronavirus-school-closures-salem-keizer-public-schools/5040931002/|title=Coronavirus: Oregon schools close, doctors demand state action, warming shelter closed|first1=Whitney|last1=Woodworth|first2=Virginia|last2=Barreda|date=March 13, 2020|newspaper=[[Statesman Journal]]|location=Salem, Oregon|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Masses were canceled until April 14, which included Holy Week and Easter. Archbishop Sample said the announcement was \"by far one of the most difficult communications [he has] ever written\".<ref>{{cite news |title=PUBLIC MASSES HALTED TO SLOW VIRUS |url=https://catholicsentinel.org/Content/News/Local/Article/PUBLIC-MASSES-HALTED-TO-SLOW-VIRUS/2/35/39515 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Catholic Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Portland in Oregon]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> [[The Grotto]] has suspended Mass until March 31, but visitors are welcome to visit the outdoor sanctuary and Upper Gardens.<ref name=Stein/>\n\n==Crime==\nOn March 23, the [[Multnomah County Sheriff's Office]]'s said the crime rate for the month to date was lower than the rate for March 2019. The agency also reported lower jail bookings and moved some inmates at the Inverness Jail in northeast Portland into temporary dormitory-style housing to follow social distancing measures.<ref name=\"Crime\">{{cite news |last1=Heye |first1=Bob |title=Coronavirus and Crime: Jail releases, a rash of break-ins and one encouraging trend |url=https://katu.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-and-crime-jail-releases-a-rash-of-break-ins-and-one-encouraging-trend |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KATU |agency=Sinclair Broadcast Group |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[KATU]] reported on a string of business break-ins in the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=Crime/> The crisis group Call to Safety, which supports people experiencing [[domestic violence]], began receiving twice as many calls and more requests for shelter and other resources once stay-at-home orders were enforced.<ref name=\"domeshelter\">{{cite news |last1=Crombie |first1=Noelle |title=Calls to Oregon's domestic violence crisis lines spike amid coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/crime/2020/03/calls-to-oregons-domestic-violence-crisis-lines-spike-amid-coronavirus-crisis.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Oregonian |publisher=Advance Local Media |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Thousands of [[respirator]] masks valued at approximately $2,500 were stolen from the Rebuilding Center in north Portland in March. Some of the masks were recovered and donated to local hospitals.<ref name=Crime/><ref name=\"stealmask\">{{cite news |author1=Nexstar Media Wire |title=Thousands of stolen N95 masks recovered in Portland, donated |url=https://www.ksn.com/news/thousands-of-stolen-n95-masks-recovered-donated/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=KSN |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other responses==\nOn March 27, Portland began nightly \"solidarity cheers\" to recognize health care and other frontline workers, similar to many other cities around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/portland-urges-nightly-solidarity-cheer-for-frontline-coronavirus-workers.html|title=Portland urges nightly solidarity cheer for frontline coronavirus workers|first=Everton |last=Bailey Jr |date=March 27, 2020|work=The Oregonian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Portland, Oregon}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.travelportland.com/about-us/covid-19/|title=COVID-19 and the Portland Community|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=Travel Portland}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Zielinski |first1=Alex |title=\"I hope everything I'm telling you isn't true\": A Portland Oncology Nurse On COVID-19 |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/blogtown/2020/03/21/28177144/i-hope-everything-im-telling-you-isnt-true-a-portland-oncology-nurse-on-covid-19 |work=Portland Mercury |date=March 21, 2020}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Oregon|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:2020 in Portland, Oregon|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Oregon]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health in Oregon]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Capewearer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCases", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Portland,_Oregon"}
